WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.415 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.415 --> 00:00:04.347 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.347 --> 00:00:07.728 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.728 --> 00:00:10.940 align:middle line:90%


00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:16.040 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING:
So now let's talk

00:00:16.040 --> 00:00:20.330 align:middle line:84%
about first the
different concepts

00:00:20.330 --> 00:00:23.910 align:middle line:84%
that we have talked
about in class.

00:00:23.910 --> 00:00:27.740 align:middle line:84%
And then in the end, I'll
get to just some example

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:31.850 align:middle line:84%
of some problems that you
might face on the midterm.

00:00:31.850 --> 00:00:38.690 align:middle line:84%
So the first is this-- that
if you take a subset of Rn,

00:00:38.690 --> 00:00:49.910 align:middle line:84%
to say that A is
bounded from above,

00:00:49.910 --> 00:01:06.280 align:middle line:84%
it just means that there exists
M such that all a in A, a

00:01:06.280 --> 00:01:08.290 align:middle line:84%
is less than or
equal to M. So this

00:01:08.290 --> 00:01:12.220 align:middle line:84%
is what it means to be bounded
from above from a subset.

00:01:12.220 --> 00:01:15.720 align:middle line:90%
And now the least upper bound.

00:01:15.720 --> 00:01:18.730 align:middle line:90%


00:01:18.730 --> 00:01:22.630 align:middle line:90%
And this is a number--

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:26.920 align:middle line:90%
so M is the least--

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:52.420 align:middle line:84%
so M is a least upper bound
if M is an upper bound

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:58.667 align:middle line:90%
and any other upper bound--

00:01:58.667 --> 00:02:03.920 align:middle line:90%


00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:05.570 align:middle line:90%
let's call it M bar--

00:02:05.570 --> 00:02:08.330 align:middle line:90%


00:02:08.330 --> 00:02:15.110 align:middle line:84%
is bigger or equal
to M. So this is

00:02:15.110 --> 00:02:18.752 align:middle line:84%
what it means to be
a least upper bound.

00:02:18.752 --> 00:02:21.235 align:middle line:90%
And so the least upper bound--

00:02:21.235 --> 00:02:23.700 align:middle line:90%
so the least upper bound--

00:02:23.700 --> 00:02:27.670 align:middle line:84%
this is what you
denote by sup of A.

00:02:27.670 --> 00:02:44.030 align:middle line:84%
This here is the least
upper bound, and similarly

00:02:44.030 --> 00:02:44.830 align:middle line:90%
For lower bounds.

00:02:44.830 --> 00:02:52.685 align:middle line:90%


00:02:52.685 --> 00:02:55.120 align:middle line:84%
And the real numbers
have this property

00:02:55.120 --> 00:03:00.550 align:middle line:84%
that if a set is
bounded from above,

00:03:00.550 --> 00:03:06.700 align:middle line:84%
then there is a least upper
bound, and likewise for the set

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:10.435 align:middle line:90%
that is bounded below.

00:03:10.435 --> 00:03:11.890 align:middle line:90%
So that was sup.

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:16.345 align:middle line:84%
And we'll get to this with
the lim sup and lim inf.

00:03:16.345 --> 00:03:20.440 align:middle line:84%
I'll just review that
a little later also.

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:23.590 align:middle line:84%
But that's another
[? performance ?] [? chain. ?]

00:03:23.590 --> 00:03:28.630 align:middle line:84%
A sequence-- so another
key concept in this class

00:03:28.630 --> 00:03:30.670 align:middle line:90%
is sequence.

00:03:30.670 --> 00:03:33.825 align:middle line:84%
And let's begin with a
sequence of real numbers.

00:03:33.825 --> 00:03:39.100 align:middle line:90%


00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:49.480 align:middle line:84%
So this is a map from the
positive integers into R.

00:03:49.480 --> 00:03:51.460 align:middle line:90%
And again, we denote--

00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:59.040 align:middle line:84%
so the image-- so if you're
looking at the image of some n,

00:03:59.040 --> 00:04:04.110 align:middle line:84%
we typically denote this or
by a n or xn or something

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:08.910 align:middle line:84%
like that where we
use the subscript,

00:04:08.910 --> 00:04:13.810 align:middle line:84%
but it's just the image under
this map So that's a sequence.

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:19.219 align:middle line:84%
So for each positive integer,
you get a real number.

00:04:19.219 --> 00:04:25.500 align:middle line:90%


00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:28.470 align:middle line:84%
Then for a sequence,
one of the first things

00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:31.210 align:middle line:84%
you were interested
in is convergence.

00:04:31.210 --> 00:04:36.790 align:middle line:90%


00:04:36.790 --> 00:04:45.880 align:middle line:84%
So if this here is a sequence,
that xn converges to some x

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:57.050 align:middle line:84%
here, this here just means that
for all epsilon greater than 0,

00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:58.120 align:middle line:90%
there exists--

00:04:58.120 --> 00:04:59.510 align:middle line:90%
I will use this symbol.

00:04:59.510 --> 00:05:03.370 align:middle line:84%
I haven't used it until now, but
it's just so hard not to use it.

00:05:03.370 --> 00:05:06.100 align:middle line:90%
This here means "there exists."

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:09.550 align:middle line:90%
It's not on the midterm.

00:05:09.550 --> 00:05:11.740 align:middle line:84%
But it's a totally
standard symbol.

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:20.170 align:middle line:84%
So there exists capital N such
that if little n is bigger

00:05:20.170 --> 00:05:28.510 align:middle line:84%
or equal to capital N, then xn
minus x is smaller than epsilon.

00:05:28.510 --> 00:05:33.820 align:middle line:84%
So this is what it means for
a sequence to converge to x--

00:05:33.820 --> 00:05:35.770 align:middle line:90%
sequence xn converges to x.

00:05:35.770 --> 00:05:39.850 align:middle line:84%
And you write it like this,
or you can write xn and then

00:05:39.850 --> 00:05:43.000 align:middle line:84%
the limit here as
n goes to infinity

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:50.910 align:middle line:84%
is equal to-- both of
these are standard use.

00:05:50.910 --> 00:06:08.610 align:middle line:84%
And then also, if a sequence
is not convergent, then

00:06:08.610 --> 00:06:13.757 align:middle line:90%
we say it is divergent.

00:06:13.757 --> 00:06:16.500 align:middle line:90%


00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:21.990 align:middle line:84%
So a sequence is either
convergent, or it's divergent.

00:06:21.990 --> 00:06:29.250 align:middle line:90%
And then there's this property--

00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:34.580 align:middle line:90%
useful property, so a lemma.

00:06:34.580 --> 00:06:39.390 align:middle line:90%


00:06:39.390 --> 00:06:50.800 align:middle line:84%
If xn is convergent,
then the set--

00:06:50.800 --> 00:06:52.490 align:middle line:90%
this here is a set--

00:06:52.490 --> 00:06:55.190 align:middle line:90%
this here is a bounded set.

00:06:55.190 --> 00:07:00.775 align:middle line:90%


00:07:00.775 --> 00:07:03.490 align:middle line:90%
So we [? talked ?] about that.

00:07:03.490 --> 00:07:06.850 align:middle line:84%
And then another
thing about sequences

00:07:06.850 --> 00:07:19.790 align:middle line:84%
is the algebraic
properties of sequences.

00:07:19.790 --> 00:07:23.560 align:middle line:90%


00:07:23.560 --> 00:07:26.080 align:middle line:84%
And what are the
algebraic properties?

00:07:26.080 --> 00:07:29.860 align:middle line:84%
They are that if you take
two sequences a n and bn,

00:07:29.860 --> 00:07:36.430 align:middle line:84%
and let's say that a n converges
to a and bn converges to b.

00:07:36.430 --> 00:07:40.290 align:middle line:84%
Then the algebraic-- and
c is just a constant.

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:43.060 align:middle line:90%


00:07:43.060 --> 00:07:44.780 align:middle line:90%
Then you have that--

00:07:44.780 --> 00:07:49.680 align:middle line:84%
so-- and often, one combines--
what I did as 1 and 2 before--

00:07:49.680 --> 00:07:54.000 align:middle line:84%
you combine, and you're
looking at a n plus c times bn.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:57.810 align:middle line:84%
This here converges
to a plus cb.

00:07:57.810 --> 00:08:00.940 align:middle line:84%
This is the first in this--
and when I state it like this,

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:03.360 align:middle line:84%
it's combining two
of the 1 properties

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:06.390 align:middle line:90%
that we talked about earlier.

00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:14.460 align:middle line:84%
The second one is that a n times
bn will converge to a times b.

00:08:14.460 --> 00:08:22.500 align:middle line:84%
Third property is that if
these here are not equal to 0

00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:25.650 align:middle line:84%
and the limit here
is not equal to 0,

00:08:25.650 --> 00:08:28.710 align:middle line:84%
then 1 over a n
converges to 1/a.

00:08:28.710 --> 00:08:31.500 align:middle line:90%


00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:35.280 align:middle line:84%
And so of course, this
last one, [INAUDIBLE]--

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:38.460 align:middle line:84%
this one implies, in particular,
of course, that also,

00:08:38.460 --> 00:08:43.010 align:middle line:90%
bn over a n converges to b/a.

00:08:43.010 --> 00:08:45.680 align:middle line:84%
This is just because
this property here

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:48.080 align:middle line:90%
combined with the property 2--

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:51.740 align:middle line:90%
that will give you this.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:58.340 align:middle line:84%
So that's the algebraic
properties of limits.

00:08:58.340 --> 00:09:06.120 align:middle line:84%
Then you have the concept of a
subsequence, so a subsequence.

00:09:06.120 --> 00:09:11.810 align:middle line:90%


00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:16.190 align:middle line:84%
So we imagine that
we have a sequence.

00:09:16.190 --> 00:09:19.770 align:middle line:84%
And often we don't go all
the way back like this,

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:24.650 align:middle line:84%
but a sequence, again, is a
map from the positive integers

00:09:24.650 --> 00:09:32.810 align:middle line:84%
into R. And we denote the
image of n by, typically, xn.

00:09:32.810 --> 00:09:36.170 align:middle line:84%
Then a subsequence of
this sequence-- and this

00:09:36.170 --> 00:09:38.930 align:middle line:84%
is typically denoted
something like this, where

00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:42.630 align:middle line:90%
you have a further subscript.

00:09:42.630 --> 00:09:45.480 align:middle line:84%
And this is important,
again, that this

00:09:45.480 --> 00:09:52.840 align:middle line:84%
is equal to f of g
of k, where g here--

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:55.560 align:middle line:84%
and this is the really
important property--

00:09:55.560 --> 00:09:59.850 align:middle line:84%
that g is a map from
the positive integers

00:09:59.850 --> 00:10:01.840 align:middle line:90%
into the positive integers.

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:05.310 align:middle line:84%
And then, really
important is that g here

00:10:05.310 --> 00:10:07.480 align:middle line:90%
is strictly increasing.

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:14.190 align:middle line:90%


00:10:14.190 --> 00:10:17.310 align:middle line:84%
And so strictly
increasing guarantees you

00:10:17.310 --> 00:10:22.950 align:middle line:84%
that these numbers here are
taken in the same order as

00:10:22.950 --> 00:10:24.750 align:middle line:90%
in the original sequence.

00:10:24.750 --> 00:10:27.630 align:middle line:90%
But you may skip a bunch.

00:10:27.630 --> 00:10:29.860 align:middle line:84%
You take one, and then
you may skip a bunch,

00:10:29.860 --> 00:10:32.680 align:middle line:84%
and then you take another one,
and then you may skip more.

00:10:32.680 --> 00:10:37.260 align:middle line:84%
But it's in the same order, and
that's what strictly increasing

00:10:37.260 --> 00:10:41.000 align:middle line:90%
is guaranteeing.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:47.570 align:middle line:84%
And then you have
this property that--

00:10:47.570 --> 00:10:58.580 align:middle line:84%
so you have the theorem that
a sequence xn is convergent if

00:10:58.580 --> 00:11:15.320 align:middle line:84%
and only if all
subsequences are convergent.

00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:19.640 align:middle line:84%
And one of the two
directions for this theorem

00:11:19.640 --> 00:11:27.440 align:middle line:84%
was trivial, because
if you take a sequence,

00:11:27.440 --> 00:11:31.370 align:middle line:84%
then it is-- if you're
thinking about this map here g

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:36.090 align:middle line:84%
as being the identity, so that
would give you a subsequence,

00:11:36.090 --> 00:11:38.710 align:middle line:84%
but that really is
the original sequence.

00:11:38.710 --> 00:11:42.640 align:middle line:84%
So the original sequence
is a subsequence of itself.

00:11:42.640 --> 00:11:45.730 align:middle line:84%
So if all subsequences
are convergent, well,

00:11:45.730 --> 00:11:48.710 align:middle line:84%
then, in particular, the
sequence itself is convergent.

00:11:48.710 --> 00:11:50.520 align:middle line:84%
So one of the two
directions was trivial.

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:53.574 align:middle line:90%


00:11:53.574 --> 00:11:58.060 align:middle line:84%
Now, then we had
these two theorems,

00:11:58.060 --> 00:12:00.170 align:middle line:90%
and they were [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:00.170 --> 00:12:07.190 align:middle line:84%
So the thing in mathematics is
that things build on each other.

00:12:07.190 --> 00:12:11.150 align:middle line:84%
And hopefully, each
step is fairly trivial,

00:12:11.150 --> 00:12:13.840 align:middle line:84%
but you build step
by step, and then

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:16.720 align:middle line:84%
you end up with something
highly non-trivial.

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:22.870 align:middle line:84%
So this here was pretty trivial,
but then we used it later on

00:12:22.870 --> 00:12:25.850 align:middle line:90%
to prove something non-trivial.

00:12:25.850 --> 00:12:28.490 align:middle line:84%
So this was this monotone
convergence theorem.

00:12:28.490 --> 00:12:36.920 align:middle line:90%


00:12:36.920 --> 00:12:41.060 align:middle line:84%
And there were two
versions of this.

00:12:41.060 --> 00:12:50.840 align:middle line:84%
You had a sequence xn,
and xn was increasing.

00:12:50.840 --> 00:12:52.820 align:middle line:84%
So that means that
the next element

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:55.430 align:middle line:84%
is bigger or equal to
the previous element.

00:12:55.430 --> 00:12:58.580 align:middle line:84%
If this here was
the case, then xn

00:12:58.580 --> 00:13:13.940 align:middle line:84%
is convergent if and
only if xn is bounded--

00:13:13.940 --> 00:13:16.940 align:middle line:90%
if the sequence is bounded.

00:13:16.940 --> 00:13:21.470 align:middle line:90%
And the sup of the xn--

00:13:21.470 --> 00:13:29.060 align:middle line:90%


00:13:29.060 --> 00:13:31.020 align:middle line:90%
this here is the limit.

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:41.350 align:middle line:90%


00:13:41.350 --> 00:13:44.980 align:middle line:84%
And the second
version of this is

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:48.530 align:middle line:84%
if you have a monotone-- so
instead of being increasing,

00:13:48.530 --> 00:13:49.760 align:middle line:90%
it's now decreasing.

00:13:49.760 --> 00:13:53.000 align:middle line:84%
So the next element
is smaller or

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.795 align:middle line:90%
equal to the previous element.

00:13:55.795 --> 00:14:07.420 align:middle line:84%
And then similarly, the sequence
xn is convergent if and only

00:14:07.420 --> 00:14:23.290 align:middle line:90%
if xn is bounded from below.

00:14:23.290 --> 00:14:25.130 align:middle line:90%
And in this case--

00:14:25.130 --> 00:14:29.260 align:middle line:84%
and if it is bounded from
below, then the limit here,

00:14:29.260 --> 00:14:33.690 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE] of xn is the inf.

00:14:33.690 --> 00:14:36.620 align:middle line:90%


00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:39.290 align:middle line:84%
So that was the monotone
convergence theorem.

00:14:39.290 --> 00:14:42.950 align:middle line:84%
And it has these two versions,
the increasing version

00:14:42.950 --> 00:14:46.160 align:middle line:90%
and the decreasing version.

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:55.340 align:middle line:84%
Then another important concept
was that of the Cauchy sequence.

00:14:55.340 --> 00:15:00.980 align:middle line:84%
And the reason why
Cauchy sequence

00:15:00.980 --> 00:15:05.390 align:middle line:84%
is useful even for
the real numbers--

00:15:05.390 --> 00:15:08.210 align:middle line:84%
later on, we generalize
these concepts--

00:15:08.210 --> 00:15:11.360 align:middle line:84%
the most obvious [INAUDIBLE]
of the concept of

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:14.330 align:middle line:84%
convergence, but also of
that of being a Cauchy

00:15:14.330 --> 00:15:16.490 align:middle line:90%
sequence-- to metric spaces.

00:15:16.490 --> 00:15:21.190 align:middle line:84%
But even for the real
numbers, Cauchy sequence--

00:15:21.190 --> 00:15:24.590 align:middle line:84%
you might be interested
in whether a sequence is

00:15:24.590 --> 00:15:28.610 align:middle line:84%
convergent, but sometimes
it's much easier

00:15:28.610 --> 00:15:31.280 align:middle line:84%
to prove that it's
a Cauchy sequence

00:15:31.280 --> 00:15:33.490 align:middle line:84%
than to prove that it
actually is convergent.

00:15:33.490 --> 00:15:37.340 align:middle line:84%
And so if you don't really
care about what the limit is,

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:42.660 align:middle line:84%
then it's often easier to prove
that it's a Cauchy sequence.

00:15:42.660 --> 00:15:47.020 align:middle line:90%


00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:51.260 align:middle line:84%
So Cauchy sequence--
so you have a sequence.

00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:55.900 align:middle line:84%
Again, we're still
in the real numbers.

00:15:55.900 --> 00:15:58.660 align:middle line:90%
And this is a Cauchy sequence.

00:15:58.660 --> 00:16:00.820 align:middle line:90%
It just means that for all--

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:04.180 align:middle line:84%
and now I will use
also this here.

00:16:04.180 --> 00:16:06.530 align:middle line:84%
This symbol just
means "for all,"

00:16:06.530 --> 00:16:08.270 align:middle line:84%
and that's also a
standard symbol.

00:16:08.270 --> 00:16:10.900 align:middle line:90%
It's an inverted A.

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:15.580 align:middle line:84%
For all epsilon greater
than 0, there exists--

00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:22.750 align:middle line:84%
again, this here-- the inverted
E means "there exists"--

00:16:22.750 --> 00:16:23.650 align:middle line:90%
delta-- I'm sorry.

00:16:23.650 --> 00:16:34.950 align:middle line:84%
There exists capital N such
that if little n and little m

00:16:34.950 --> 00:16:39.060 align:middle line:84%
are bigger than capital
N, then those two elements

00:16:39.060 --> 00:16:45.480 align:middle line:84%
are bunched epsilon close
together [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:45.480 --> 00:16:51.690 align:middle line:84%
This is what it means for a
sequence to be Cauchy sequence--

00:16:51.690 --> 00:16:55.745 align:middle line:84%
that the tail of the sequence
lies very, very close together.

00:16:55.745 --> 00:16:58.710 align:middle line:90%


00:16:58.710 --> 00:17:06.780 align:middle line:90%
Then let me skip.

00:17:06.780 --> 00:17:09.027 align:middle line:84%
In my notes, I have
something about contracting,

00:17:09.027 --> 00:17:11.319 align:middle line:84%
but actually, there won't be
anything about contracting

00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:13.060 align:middle line:90%
methods, so I'll skip that.

00:17:13.060 --> 00:17:20.130 align:middle line:90%


00:17:20.130 --> 00:17:24.630 align:middle line:84%
Let me now next talk about
the Cauchy convergence

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:29.160 align:middle line:84%
theorem and the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:40.000 align:middle line:90%


00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:53.020 align:middle line:84%
So Cauchy-- also let me
just remind you that, again,

00:17:53.020 --> 00:17:54.080 align:middle line:90%
on the midterm--

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:56.500 align:middle line:84%
so there are these
five main problems.

00:17:56.500 --> 00:17:58.870 align:middle line:84%
Then there's the
six bonus problems.

00:17:58.870 --> 00:18:03.180 align:middle line:90%
But make sure that you--

00:18:03.180 --> 00:18:05.330 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't matter
which one you do,

00:18:05.330 --> 00:18:09.370 align:middle line:84%
so you might as well
start with the ones that

00:18:09.370 --> 00:18:14.710 align:middle line:90%
seems easiest to you.

00:18:14.710 --> 00:18:18.400 align:middle line:84%
And you can see, anyway, it says
exactly how many points each

00:18:18.400 --> 00:18:20.690 align:middle line:90%
of them get, so you can--

00:18:20.690 --> 00:18:24.490 align:middle line:84%
if you don't have enough
time to finish all of it,

00:18:24.490 --> 00:18:26.740 align:middle line:84%
you can be sure to
try to optimize.

00:18:26.740 --> 00:18:29.350 align:middle line:90%


00:18:29.350 --> 00:18:31.360 align:middle line:84%
So what is the Cauchy
convergence here?

00:18:31.360 --> 00:18:36.645 align:middle line:84%
So again, we are in
Rn-- [? R, ?] sorry.

00:18:36.645 --> 00:18:38.800 align:middle line:90%
And we have n.

00:18:38.800 --> 00:18:42.180 align:middle line:84%
So the Cauchy convergence
theorem [INAUDIBLE] theorem.

00:18:42.180 --> 00:18:58.000 align:middle line:84%
Let's say that if xn is a Cauchy
sequence, then xn is convergent.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.160 align:middle line:90%


00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:05.160 align:middle line:84%
That's the Cauchy
convergence theorem.

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:14.310 align:middle line:84%
The Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem-- and this Cauchy

00:19:14.310 --> 00:19:17.220 align:middle line:84%
convergence-- we
talked about that.

00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:21.920 align:middle line:84%
So the concepts--
when we in a minute

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:26.720 align:middle line:84%
review metric spaces, then
convergent sequence-- that

00:19:26.720 --> 00:19:28.310 align:middle line:90%
makes sense in a metric space.

00:19:28.310 --> 00:19:33.020 align:middle line:84%
Cauchy sequence makes
sense in a metric space.

00:19:33.020 --> 00:19:36.590 align:middle line:84%
But it's not-- and the
statement of this theorem

00:19:36.590 --> 00:19:40.730 align:middle line:84%
makes sense in a metric
space, but it's not always

00:19:40.730 --> 00:19:41.760 align:middle line:90%
that it's true.

00:19:41.760 --> 00:19:46.370 align:middle line:84%
It holds in R, but it doesn't
hold in a general metric space.

00:19:46.370 --> 00:19:53.390 align:middle line:84%
The Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem-- statement of that

00:19:53.390 --> 00:19:55.890 align:middle line:84%
also makes sense in a
general metric space,

00:19:55.890 --> 00:19:59.420 align:middle line:84%
but it doesn't hold in
a general metric space.

00:19:59.420 --> 00:20:04.780 align:middle line:84%
So these are-- again, these are
things about the real numbers.

00:20:04.780 --> 00:20:07.580 align:middle line:90%


00:20:07.580 --> 00:20:09.800 align:middle line:84%
They extend to more
than the real numbers,

00:20:09.800 --> 00:20:12.240 align:middle line:84%
but you have to--
for other spaces,

00:20:12.240 --> 00:20:16.660 align:middle line:84%
you have to prove
it individually.

00:20:16.660 --> 00:20:18.920 align:middle line:84%
So Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem says

00:20:18.920 --> 00:20:28.860 align:middle line:84%
that if xn is a
bounded sequence,

00:20:28.860 --> 00:20:35.710 align:middle line:84%
then xn has a
convergent subsequence.

00:20:35.710 --> 00:20:43.100 align:middle line:90%


00:20:43.100 --> 00:20:44.850 align:middle line:84%
So that's the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:20:44.850 --> 00:20:50.400 align:middle line:90%


00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:52.830 align:middle line:84%
The next thing I
want to review is

00:20:52.830 --> 00:20:55.640 align:middle line:84%
what it means for a
function to be continuous.

00:20:55.640 --> 00:20:58.930 align:middle line:84%
So continuity is another
important property.

00:20:58.930 --> 00:21:03.390 align:middle line:84%
It's closely tied together
with [INAUDIBLE] sequence,

00:21:03.390 --> 00:21:05.075 align:middle line:84%
and we'll get to that
in just a minute.

00:21:05.075 --> 00:21:24.488 align:middle line:90%


00:21:24.488 --> 00:21:27.320 align:middle line:90%
So if you have a function--

00:21:27.320 --> 00:21:31.400 align:middle line:84%
let's say on R, but it could
be defined on a subset of R.

00:21:31.400 --> 00:21:33.440 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
function like this,

00:21:33.440 --> 00:21:47.020 align:middle line:84%
then we say that f here is
continuous at x0 if for all--

00:21:47.020 --> 00:21:50.930 align:middle line:90%


00:21:50.930 --> 00:21:58.400 align:middle line:84%
it's continuous at x0 if for
all epsilon greater than 0,

00:21:58.400 --> 00:22:11.900 align:middle line:84%
there exists a delta greater
than 0 such that, if x minus x0

00:22:11.900 --> 00:22:21.800 align:middle line:84%
is smaller than delta, then the
images are smaller than epsilon.

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:27.070 align:middle line:90%


00:22:27.070 --> 00:22:30.470 align:middle line:84%
So that's what it means for
a function to be continuous.

00:22:30.470 --> 00:22:38.830 align:middle line:84%
And there was this theorem or
lemma that tied things together.

00:22:38.830 --> 00:23:03.250 align:middle line:84%
So lemma-- if f is continuous
at x0 and xn converges to x0,

00:23:03.250 --> 00:23:09.590 align:middle line:84%
then the images of
this sequences--

00:23:09.590 --> 00:23:11.560 align:middle line:90%
so that's another sequence--

00:23:11.560 --> 00:23:15.380 align:middle line:90%
converge to f of x0.

00:23:15.380 --> 00:23:18.540 align:middle line:84%
So we proved this even
in a metric space,

00:23:18.540 --> 00:23:26.090 align:middle line:84%
but remember that
we're still in R.

00:23:26.090 --> 00:23:31.380 align:middle line:84%
And then we had the algebraic
properties of functions,

00:23:31.380 --> 00:23:34.340 align:middle line:84%
and they were very
similar to this.

00:23:34.340 --> 00:23:36.440 align:middle line:90%
So let me just review them--

00:23:36.440 --> 00:24:01.680 align:middle line:84%
so algebraic properties
of continuous functions.

00:24:01.680 --> 00:24:08.300 align:middle line:90%


00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:13.760 align:middle line:84%
So imagine that you have f and
g are continuous functions.

00:24:13.760 --> 00:24:18.044 align:middle line:90%


00:24:18.044 --> 00:24:22.300 align:middle line:84%
[INAUDIBLE] everything
is defined on R.

00:24:22.300 --> 00:24:26.140 align:middle line:90%
c here is a constant.

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:31.060 align:middle line:84%
Well, then, property 1 that
corresponds to that property 1

00:24:31.060 --> 00:24:35.890 align:middle line:84%
is that this function plus
c times this function here--

00:24:35.890 --> 00:24:37.910 align:middle line:90%
this here is also continuous.

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:44.380 align:middle line:90%


00:24:44.380 --> 00:24:50.500 align:middle line:84%
And then 2 is that if this
function here is never

00:24:50.500 --> 00:24:55.720 align:middle line:84%
equal to 0, then 1
over this function

00:24:55.720 --> 00:24:58.430 align:middle line:90%
here is also continuous.

00:24:58.430 --> 00:25:01.330 align:middle line:90%


00:25:01.330 --> 00:25:03.700 align:middle line:84%
And then-- sorry,
that was not the--

00:25:03.700 --> 00:25:07.660 align:middle line:84%
sorry, I should make that
the third property-- sorry--

00:25:07.660 --> 00:25:12.500 align:middle line:84%
that f times g is
also continuous.

00:25:12.500 --> 00:25:14.720 align:middle line:84%
And then the third
property would

00:25:14.720 --> 00:25:19.250 align:middle line:84%
be that if f is not
equal to 0, [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:19.250 --> 00:25:21.630 align:middle line:84%
Then this function here
is also continuous.

00:25:21.630 --> 00:25:24.750 align:middle line:90%


00:25:24.750 --> 00:25:26.810 align:middle line:90%
And again, I divided it up.

00:25:26.810 --> 00:25:29.240 align:middle line:84%
When I did it, I divided
it up into four steps

00:25:29.240 --> 00:25:34.010 align:middle line:84%
because I separated
this out as two steps.

00:25:34.010 --> 00:25:37.820 align:middle line:84%
And so from this one,
we got that by-- just

00:25:37.820 --> 00:25:41.690 align:middle line:84%
because then we proved that the
constant function was continuous

00:25:41.690 --> 00:25:45.470 align:middle line:84%
and the linear function, the
function f of x equal to x,

00:25:45.470 --> 00:25:46.820 align:middle line:90%
is continuous.

00:25:46.820 --> 00:25:51.320 align:middle line:84%
Once we had that, then
we just use 1 and 2

00:25:51.320 --> 00:25:58.100 align:middle line:84%
here to prove that all
polynomials continuous.

00:25:58.100 --> 00:26:00.740 align:middle line:84%
And then if we
bring in 3, then we

00:26:00.740 --> 00:26:05.120 align:middle line:84%
have this with all rational
functions are continuous except,

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:08.748 align:middle line:84%
of course, where the denominator
vanishes [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:08.748 --> 00:26:11.566 align:middle line:90%


00:26:11.566 --> 00:26:15.100 align:middle line:84%
So that was how you built
continuous functions

00:26:15.100 --> 00:26:19.870 align:middle line:90%
from non-continuous functions.

00:26:19.870 --> 00:26:24.550 align:middle line:84%
Then we proved the extreme
value and the intermediate value

00:26:24.550 --> 00:26:25.100 align:middle line:90%
theorem.

00:26:25.100 --> 00:26:26.560 align:middle line:90%
We had these two theorems.

00:26:26.560 --> 00:26:27.800 align:middle line:90%
And they were proved--

00:26:27.800 --> 00:26:30.760 align:middle line:84%
so one way to prove it
that we did last time

00:26:30.760 --> 00:26:37.540 align:middle line:84%
was to use this lemma
that tied together

00:26:37.540 --> 00:26:40.390 align:middle line:90%
continuity and sequences.

00:26:40.390 --> 00:26:45.010 align:middle line:84%
And so we had the
extreme value theorem.

00:26:45.010 --> 00:26:48.580 align:middle line:84%
And this just says that if you
have a function-- but now it's

00:26:48.580 --> 00:26:53.560 align:middle line:84%
crucial that this here
is a bounded interval

00:26:53.560 --> 00:26:56.990 align:middle line:84%
and the endpoints
are included in this.

00:26:56.990 --> 00:26:59.290 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a
function like this

00:26:59.290 --> 00:27:05.730 align:middle line:84%
and the function
is continuous, then

00:27:05.730 --> 00:27:10.050 align:middle line:84%
the sup and the inf
over the set here--

00:27:10.050 --> 00:27:19.270 align:middle line:84%
this achieves a max or, if you
would, max of f and min of f

00:27:19.270 --> 00:27:19.890 align:middle line:90%
are achieved.

00:27:19.890 --> 00:27:24.690 align:middle line:90%


00:27:24.690 --> 00:27:28.530 align:middle line:84%
In particular, the
function is bounded.

00:27:28.530 --> 00:27:31.890 align:middle line:84%
So I'll just state it like this,
a little bit brief like that.

00:27:31.890 --> 00:27:34.390 align:middle line:84%
So that was the
extreme value theorem.

00:27:34.390 --> 00:27:37.410 align:middle line:90%
The intermediate value theorem--

00:27:37.410 --> 00:27:40.410 align:middle line:84%
it said that if you
have a function--

00:27:40.410 --> 00:27:43.950 align:middle line:84%
imagine it starting off
here and it ending there.

00:27:43.950 --> 00:27:46.260 align:middle line:90%
So this is like a function.

00:27:46.260 --> 00:27:48.300 align:middle line:84%
The intermediate
value theorem says

00:27:48.300 --> 00:27:51.360 align:middle line:84%
that everything in
between these two

00:27:51.360 --> 00:27:54.760 align:middle line:90%
is also the image of something.

00:27:54.760 --> 00:28:01.260 align:middle line:84%
So if-- let's say that f of
a is smaller than f of b.

00:28:01.260 --> 00:28:08.800 align:middle line:84%
Then f y here is between
f of a and f of b,

00:28:08.800 --> 00:28:16.810 align:middle line:84%
then there exists x between
a and b so that f of x

00:28:16.810 --> 00:28:18.250 align:middle line:90%
is equal to y.

00:28:18.250 --> 00:28:22.220 align:middle line:84%
Again, the functions we
talk about are continuous,

00:28:22.220 --> 00:28:26.230 align:middle line:84%
and they are defined on
this [? closed ?] interval--

00:28:26.230 --> 00:28:28.915 align:middle line:90%
this interval.

00:28:28.915 --> 00:28:30.540 align:middle line:90%
So that was those two theorems.

00:28:30.540 --> 00:28:33.100 align:middle line:90%


00:28:33.100 --> 00:28:40.630 align:middle line:84%
And they used some
property about that--

00:28:40.630 --> 00:28:42.430 align:middle line:90%
they used two things.

00:28:42.430 --> 00:28:47.680 align:middle line:84%
They used the
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem,

00:28:47.680 --> 00:28:50.920 align:middle line:84%
and then they used how sequences
and continuous functions

00:28:50.920 --> 00:28:52.150 align:middle line:90%
were tied together.

00:28:52.150 --> 00:28:56.215 align:middle line:84%
The Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem
is using something about

00:28:56.215 --> 00:28:58.670 align:middle line:84%
that the real
numbers are ordered

00:28:58.670 --> 00:29:02.670 align:middle line:84%
and like this with
sup and inf [? R. ?]

00:29:02.670 --> 00:29:05.655 align:middle line:84%
You have the least upper bound
property and the greatest lower

00:29:05.655 --> 00:29:06.280 align:middle line:90%
bound property.

00:29:06.280 --> 00:29:09.640 align:middle line:90%


00:29:09.640 --> 00:29:13.350 align:middle line:84%
Now another thing--
so we talked about--

00:29:13.350 --> 00:29:17.670 align:middle line:84%
so some of the highlights
in terms of concepts

00:29:17.670 --> 00:29:22.770 align:middle line:84%
are sequences and
continuity of functions,

00:29:22.770 --> 00:29:26.410 align:middle line:84%
and then various properties
that follow from this.

00:29:26.410 --> 00:29:30.720 align:middle line:90%
Then another thing is series.

00:29:30.720 --> 00:29:34.940 align:middle line:90%
So that's another key concept.

00:29:34.940 --> 00:29:44.940 align:middle line:90%


00:29:44.940 --> 00:29:49.760 align:middle line:84%
A series is where you're
starting with a sequence.

00:29:49.760 --> 00:29:55.560 align:middle line:90%


00:29:55.560 --> 00:30:01.580 align:middle line:84%
So series-- so you're
starting with-- so this here

00:30:01.580 --> 00:30:02.815 align:middle line:90%
is a sequence.

00:30:02.815 --> 00:30:06.290 align:middle line:90%


00:30:06.290 --> 00:30:12.470 align:middle line:84%
And now you form
another sequence Sn.

00:30:12.470 --> 00:30:15.290 align:middle line:84%
But here you're summing,
and it could start

00:30:15.290 --> 00:30:17.360 align:middle line:90%
wherever you want to start it.

00:30:17.360 --> 00:30:19.820 align:middle line:90%
Let's say it starts from 0.

00:30:19.820 --> 00:30:21.450 align:middle line:90%
You're summing the first--

00:30:21.450 --> 00:30:24.200 align:middle line:84%
in this case, it would be--
because you're starting at 0,

00:30:24.200 --> 00:30:27.140 align:middle line:84%
you're summing the
first n plus 1.

00:30:27.140 --> 00:30:36.230 align:middle line:84%
So a i-- this is a0 plus a n--
sorry, n plus 1 in this case.

00:30:36.230 --> 00:30:38.330 align:middle line:84%
But you don't have
to start at 0.

00:30:38.330 --> 00:30:41.960 align:middle line:84%
If you started at 1, it
would be the first n numbers.

00:30:41.960 --> 00:30:45.622 align:middle line:84%
So you're looking at--
so a series is really

00:30:45.622 --> 00:30:48.080 align:middle line:84%
kind of the same thing, but
you think about it a little bit

00:30:48.080 --> 00:30:50.270 align:middle line:84%
different, but it's really the
same thing as a sequence, where

00:30:50.270 --> 00:30:51.937 align:middle line:84%
you're starting with
a sequence and then

00:30:51.937 --> 00:30:54.110 align:middle line:90%
you form a new sequence.

00:30:54.110 --> 00:30:58.360 align:middle line:84%
And then the key question
here is-- so key question--

00:30:58.360 --> 00:31:06.180 align:middle line:90%


00:31:06.180 --> 00:31:12.040 align:middle line:90%
is a series convergent or not?

00:31:12.040 --> 00:31:18.960 align:middle line:90%


00:31:18.960 --> 00:31:23.160 align:middle line:90%
And so that's a key question.

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:26.340 align:middle line:84%
And if it is convergent--
and you often--

00:31:26.340 --> 00:31:31.110 align:middle line:84%
the series is often
written like this.

00:31:31.110 --> 00:31:36.450 align:middle line:84%
And so this here will
symbolize the series.

00:31:36.450 --> 00:31:39.150 align:middle line:84%
And if the series
is convergent, it

00:31:39.150 --> 00:31:42.695 align:middle line:84%
will also symbolize the
limit, so it has two meanings.

00:31:42.695 --> 00:31:46.330 align:middle line:90%


00:31:46.330 --> 00:31:49.100 align:middle line:84%
But even if it's not convergent,
then it [? worked. ?]

00:31:49.100 --> 00:31:51.570 align:middle line:84%
Well, if it's not convergent,
you would just write down--

00:31:51.570 --> 00:31:56.030 align:middle line:84%
and you would think
about this as a series.

00:31:56.030 --> 00:32:05.150 align:middle line:84%
Now, there are some series that
are of particular importance,

00:32:05.150 --> 00:32:09.260 align:middle line:84%
and they can then be used
to determine whether or not

00:32:09.260 --> 00:32:13.190 align:middle line:90%
other series are convergent.

00:32:13.190 --> 00:32:14.640 align:middle line:90%
So let me just review them.

00:32:14.640 --> 00:32:18.430 align:middle line:84%
And the most important of
all is the geometric series.

00:32:18.430 --> 00:32:25.610 align:middle line:90%


00:32:25.610 --> 00:32:34.940 align:middle line:84%
And the geometric series is the
series c to the n, n equal to 0

00:32:34.940 --> 00:32:41.670 align:middle line:84%
to infinity, and your c is just
some fixed number, real number,

00:32:41.670 --> 00:32:44.780 align:middle line:90%
and you're looking at this.

00:32:44.780 --> 00:32:48.950 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
geometric series,

00:32:48.950 --> 00:33:00.580 align:middle line:84%
and this is convergent if
the absolute value of c

00:33:00.580 --> 00:33:04.296 align:middle line:84%
is less than 1 and
divergent otherwise.

00:33:04.296 --> 00:33:12.880 align:middle line:90%


00:33:12.880 --> 00:33:19.120 align:middle line:84%
And if it is convergent
when c in absolute value

00:33:19.120 --> 00:33:30.070 align:middle line:84%
is less than 1, then this sum
here is equal to 1 minus c.

00:33:30.070 --> 00:33:32.420 align:middle line:90%
But remember two things.

00:33:32.420 --> 00:33:35.720 align:middle line:84%
One is that when you actually
want to evaluate the sum,

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:37.790 align:middle line:84%
it's crucial where
you're starting.

00:33:37.790 --> 00:33:41.990 align:middle line:84%
If I started at 1, there is
not any more equal to this.

00:33:41.990 --> 00:33:46.090 align:middle line:84%
But you have to subtract the
first element that was missing.

00:33:46.090 --> 00:33:48.770 align:middle line:84%
So it's really--
for convergence,

00:33:48.770 --> 00:33:51.880 align:middle line:84%
it doesn't matter where you
start, but for the limits,

00:33:51.880 --> 00:33:54.200 align:middle line:90%
it's key.

00:33:54.200 --> 00:33:55.320 align:middle line:90%
That's one thing.

00:33:55.320 --> 00:33:59.840 align:middle line:84%
And the other thing is
that when you-- again, we

00:33:59.840 --> 00:34:03.740 align:middle line:84%
talked about this-- that when
you're given a series, even

00:34:03.740 --> 00:34:06.470 align:middle line:84%
before there's any question,
the first thing-- when you have

00:34:06.470 --> 00:34:09.710 align:middle line:84%
a series, the first thing
you look at is, does this a n

00:34:09.710 --> 00:34:12.210 align:middle line:90%
converge to 0 or not?

00:34:12.210 --> 00:34:15.350 align:middle line:84%
If a n does not go to
0, well, the series

00:34:15.350 --> 00:34:16.909 align:middle line:90%
is not going to converge.

00:34:16.909 --> 00:34:21.890 align:middle line:84%
There's no need to
apply any fancy test.

00:34:21.890 --> 00:34:26.100 align:middle line:84%
And for a series, the
question is always

00:34:26.100 --> 00:34:27.719 align:middle line:90%
whether it's convergent or not.

00:34:27.719 --> 00:34:32.677 align:middle line:90%


00:34:32.677 --> 00:34:37.429 align:middle line:90%
So that's a geometric series.

00:34:37.429 --> 00:34:41.989 align:middle line:84%
And then there are two other
series that we talked about.

00:34:41.989 --> 00:34:43.010 align:middle line:90%
And let me just--

00:34:43.010 --> 00:34:45.949 align:middle line:90%


00:34:45.949 --> 00:34:49.690 align:middle line:84%
not only talk about, but we
also determined whether or not

00:34:49.690 --> 00:34:52.570 align:middle line:84%
they were convergent,
and then we

00:34:52.570 --> 00:34:56.239 align:middle line:84%
used them to determine whether
other series were convergent.

00:34:56.239 --> 00:34:58.870 align:middle line:90%


00:34:58.870 --> 00:35:01.810 align:middle line:84%
But again, the most
important of all of them

00:35:01.810 --> 00:35:03.250 align:middle line:90%
is the geometric series.

00:35:03.250 --> 00:35:06.700 align:middle line:84%
That's the one that
we used to determine

00:35:06.700 --> 00:35:10.730 align:middle line:84%
whether power series in
general was convergent.

00:35:10.730 --> 00:35:13.570 align:middle line:84%
But there are two others
that are worth mentioning.

00:35:13.570 --> 00:35:15.120 align:middle line:90%
One is the harmonic series.

00:35:15.120 --> 00:35:20.410 align:middle line:90%


00:35:20.410 --> 00:35:26.410 align:middle line:84%
The harmonic series is the
series that is summing 1/n.

00:35:26.410 --> 00:35:28.250 align:middle line:90%
So this here is divergent.

00:35:28.250 --> 00:35:31.210 align:middle line:90%


00:35:31.210 --> 00:35:34.510 align:middle line:90%
So this follows second.

00:35:34.510 --> 00:35:39.160 align:middle line:84%
And then there is
a closely related--

00:35:39.160 --> 00:35:41.860 align:middle line:90%
let's call it 2 and 1/2.

00:35:41.860 --> 00:35:44.492 align:middle line:84%
That's called the
alternating harmonic series.

00:35:44.492 --> 00:35:53.840 align:middle line:90%


00:35:53.840 --> 00:35:58.100 align:middle line:84%
So the alternating was that it
was like the harmonic series,

00:35:58.100 --> 00:36:00.450 align:middle line:84%
but the sign of it
was alternating.

00:36:00.450 --> 00:36:03.800 align:middle line:90%


00:36:03.800 --> 00:36:06.000 align:middle line:84%
And this here is
actually convergent.

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:09.080 align:middle line:90%


00:36:09.080 --> 00:36:16.080 align:middle line:84%
And then-- so there's 1, 2, 2
and 1/2, and then there's 3,

00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:22.550 align:middle line:90%
and that's this series here.

00:36:22.550 --> 00:36:26.638 align:middle line:84%
We looked at this series here,
and this series was convergent.

00:36:26.638 --> 00:36:30.470 align:middle line:90%


00:36:30.470 --> 00:36:33.815 align:middle line:84%
The only one where we
determine what the sum was,

00:36:33.815 --> 00:36:35.680 align:middle line:84%
was actually the
geometric series.

00:36:35.680 --> 00:36:40.355 align:middle line:90%


00:36:40.355 --> 00:36:43.225 align:middle line:90%
So that's some key series.

00:36:43.225 --> 00:36:56.800 align:middle line:90%


00:36:56.800 --> 00:36:59.710 align:middle line:84%
Then there is-- when
you have a series,

00:36:59.710 --> 00:37:03.940 align:middle line:84%
there was one concept that
proved to be quite useful,

00:37:03.940 --> 00:37:12.112 align:middle line:84%
and that was the concept
of absolute convergence

00:37:12.112 --> 00:37:15.400 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE].

00:37:15.400 --> 00:37:19.060 align:middle line:84%
And so you were
looking at a series.

00:37:19.060 --> 00:37:27.050 align:middle line:84%
And absolute convergence
was that this sum here

00:37:27.050 --> 00:37:28.360 align:middle line:90%
was convergent.

00:37:28.360 --> 00:37:39.430 align:middle line:84%
So this here is absolute
convergent if this series,

00:37:39.430 --> 00:37:42.850 align:middle line:84%
where you just-- the a n is
replaced by the absolute value--

00:37:42.850 --> 00:37:44.200 align:middle line:90%
is convergent.

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:48.570 align:middle line:84%
So of course, for a series
of non-negative numbers,

00:37:48.570 --> 00:37:51.150 align:middle line:84%
it's automatically--
if it's convergent,

00:37:51.150 --> 00:37:54.150 align:middle line:84%
it's automatically
absolute convergent.

00:37:54.150 --> 00:37:59.226 align:middle line:84%
And we talked about
it a little bit

00:37:59.226 --> 00:38:02.160 align:middle line:84%
that one of the things
about an absolute convergent

00:38:02.160 --> 00:38:06.430 align:middle line:84%
is that you could reorder the
way you're summing things,

00:38:06.430 --> 00:38:09.090 align:middle line:84%
and it wouldn't
matter for the limit.

00:38:09.090 --> 00:38:12.658 align:middle line:84%
But if it's not absolute
convergence that really matters.

00:38:12.658 --> 00:38:13.450 align:middle line:90%
We talked about it.

00:38:13.450 --> 00:38:15.130 align:middle line:84%
We didn't really
prove anything there,

00:38:15.130 --> 00:38:18.720 align:middle line:84%
but I think it was clear
that you could do this.

00:38:18.720 --> 00:38:21.540 align:middle line:84%
One thing where we used
it was when we looked

00:38:21.540 --> 00:38:23.640 align:middle line:90%
at the product of series.

00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:27.870 align:middle line:84%
Then the product of series
was convergent if each of them

00:38:27.870 --> 00:38:29.350 align:middle line:90%
was absolute convergence.

00:38:29.350 --> 00:38:33.240 align:middle line:84%
And there you saw that we
estimated some remainder term.

00:38:33.240 --> 00:38:36.420 align:middle line:84%
And there, it was
really key that we

00:38:36.420 --> 00:38:39.226 align:middle line:90%
had absolute convergence.

00:38:39.226 --> 00:38:42.100 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so absolute
convergence is an important--

00:38:42.100 --> 00:38:45.010 align:middle line:90%


00:38:45.010 --> 00:38:48.710 align:middle line:84%
for series, it's a stronger
property than convergence,

00:38:48.710 --> 00:38:52.160 align:middle line:84%
so absolute convergence
implies convergence.

00:38:52.160 --> 00:38:54.280 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I should write
this as a theorem.

00:38:54.280 --> 00:38:57.193 align:middle line:84%
So we had the theorem--
so absolute convergence.

00:38:57.193 --> 00:39:03.820 align:middle line:90%


00:39:03.820 --> 00:39:07.242 align:middle line:84%
So this implies convergent,
but it's stronger.

00:39:07.242 --> 00:39:08.325 align:middle line:90%
In general, it's stronger.

00:39:08.325 --> 00:39:11.620 align:middle line:90%


00:39:11.620 --> 00:39:17.590 align:middle line:84%
And now-- then we
had some tests.

00:39:17.590 --> 00:39:18.860 align:middle line:90%
Then we had some tests.

00:39:18.860 --> 00:39:23.560 align:middle line:84%
And so we talked in
particular about--

00:39:23.560 --> 00:39:27.010 align:middle line:84%
there were a few other
[? tests ?] that we talked

00:39:27.010 --> 00:39:30.620 align:middle line:90%
about, but I didn't--

00:39:30.620 --> 00:39:34.210 align:middle line:84%
they're not actually going
to be on the midterm.

00:39:34.210 --> 00:39:37.030 align:middle line:84%
And some of them,
we'll get back to.

00:39:37.030 --> 00:39:40.530 align:middle line:84%
This one here won't be on the
midterm [INAUDIBLE] alternating.

00:39:40.530 --> 00:39:43.920 align:middle line:84%
But we talked about how to
improve the convergence.

00:39:43.920 --> 00:39:47.400 align:middle line:84%
And the important-- and
when we talked about it,

00:39:47.400 --> 00:39:50.700 align:middle line:84%
then we discovered
that this thing here--

00:39:50.700 --> 00:39:53.520 align:middle line:84%
that there was a stronger
statement that if you have

00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:58.800 align:middle line:84%
alternating and the a n are all
non-negative and these guys,

00:39:58.800 --> 00:40:00.480 align:middle line:90%
it's decreasing--

00:40:00.480 --> 00:40:03.390 align:middle line:90%
goes decreasing down to 0--

00:40:03.390 --> 00:40:09.141 align:middle line:84%
then actually, any
alternating sequence like that

00:40:09.141 --> 00:40:11.550 align:middle line:90%
would be convergent.

00:40:11.550 --> 00:40:15.510 align:middle line:84%
Anyway-- but for the test
we really talked about

00:40:15.510 --> 00:40:17.190 align:middle line:90%
was two tests.

00:40:17.190 --> 00:40:18.695 align:middle line:90%
One of them had two parts.

00:40:18.695 --> 00:40:23.010 align:middle line:90%


00:40:23.010 --> 00:40:27.630 align:middle line:84%
And then, in a minute, we'll
talk about how we apply them

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:31.840 align:middle line:90%
to power series, [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:31.840 --> 00:40:40.700 align:middle line:84%
So we had some
tests to determine

00:40:40.700 --> 00:40:44.305 align:middle line:90%
whether or not a series--

00:40:44.305 --> 00:40:52.470 align:middle line:90%
or not-- a series is convergent.

00:40:52.470 --> 00:40:57.180 align:middle line:90%


00:40:57.180 --> 00:40:58.290 align:middle line:90%
So what are the tests?

00:40:58.290 --> 00:41:00.475 align:middle line:84%
So there are the
comparison tests.

00:41:00.475 --> 00:41:03.920 align:middle line:90%


00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:06.740 align:middle line:84%
Let me just first
write down the test.

00:41:06.740 --> 00:41:09.650 align:middle line:84%
So the comparison test-- and
there was two versions, version

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:19.640 align:middle line:84%
A and version B. Then
there was the ratio test,

00:41:19.640 --> 00:41:21.400 align:middle line:84%
and then there
was the root test.

00:41:21.400 --> 00:41:28.820 align:middle line:90%


00:41:28.820 --> 00:41:31.050 align:middle line:84%
The ratio test and
the root test--

00:41:31.050 --> 00:41:36.390 align:middle line:84%
they are both offsprings
of the geometric series.

00:41:36.390 --> 00:41:39.780 align:middle line:84%
In both of these, you
got-- let's just talk

00:41:39.780 --> 00:41:41.850 align:middle line:90%
about these first.

00:41:41.850 --> 00:41:45.780 align:middle line:84%
The ratio test was when
we were looking at this--

00:41:45.780 --> 00:41:54.270 align:middle line:90%
the ratio of a n plus 1 over an.

00:41:54.270 --> 00:41:59.070 align:middle line:84%
So you are implicitly assuming
that the a n does not vanish.

00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:00.270 align:middle line:90%
I'm not sure.

00:42:00.270 --> 00:42:03.120 align:middle line:90%
So you can form this ratio.

00:42:03.120 --> 00:42:07.560 align:middle line:84%
And then if this limit here
as n goes to infinity--

00:42:07.560 --> 00:42:13.530 align:middle line:84%
if this limit here
is less than 1,

00:42:13.530 --> 00:42:20.730 align:middle line:84%
then the ratio test says that
the series was convergent.

00:42:20.730 --> 00:42:26.070 align:middle line:84%
If the ratio was bigger than 1,
then this ordinary element a n

00:42:26.070 --> 00:42:28.690 align:middle line:90%
would not even go to 0.

00:42:28.690 --> 00:42:30.960 align:middle line:90%
So this here is--

00:42:30.960 --> 00:42:32.400 align:middle line:90%
so in this case here--

00:42:32.400 --> 00:42:33.930 align:middle line:90%
maybe I'll write it over here.

00:42:33.930 --> 00:42:42.200 align:middle line:90%


00:42:42.200 --> 00:42:43.735 align:middle line:90%
So for the ratio test--

00:42:43.735 --> 00:42:48.429 align:middle line:90%


00:42:48.429 --> 00:42:52.130 align:middle line:84%
so the ratio test-- you
assume that the a n--

00:42:52.130 --> 00:42:54.890 align:middle line:90%
none of the a n equals 0.

00:42:54.890 --> 00:43:00.680 align:middle line:84%
And you're looking at
a n plus 1 over a n.

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:04.670 align:middle line:90%
And if this limit here--

00:43:04.670 --> 00:43:06.230 align:middle line:90%
let's call this limit--

00:43:06.230 --> 00:43:08.130 align:middle line:84%
let's assume that
the limit exists.

00:43:08.130 --> 00:43:10.340 align:middle line:90%
Of course, it may not exist

00:43:10.340 --> 00:43:13.370 align:middle line:90%
But if the limit existed--

00:43:13.370 --> 00:43:19.260 align:middle line:90%
so if c here is less than 1--

00:43:19.260 --> 00:43:22.250 align:middle line:84%
it's always non-negative because
these are non-negative numbers--

00:43:22.250 --> 00:43:26.287 align:middle line:84%
if c is less than 1, then
the series is convergent.

00:43:26.287 --> 00:43:30.860 align:middle line:90%


00:43:30.860 --> 00:43:34.560 align:middle line:84%
If this c here is
strictly bigger than 1,

00:43:34.560 --> 00:43:41.700 align:middle line:84%
this implies that the
series is divergent.

00:43:41.700 --> 00:43:45.185 align:middle line:84%
And if the c was equal
to 1, then it's unclear--

00:43:45.185 --> 00:43:48.870 align:middle line:90%


00:43:48.870 --> 00:43:52.685 align:middle line:84%
and so unclear, which means
that further tests are needed.

00:43:52.685 --> 00:43:55.320 align:middle line:90%


00:43:55.320 --> 00:44:02.320 align:middle line:84%
And so now-- so
that's the ratio test.

00:44:02.320 --> 00:44:04.220 align:middle line:90%
And the root test was similar.

00:44:04.220 --> 00:44:06.870 align:middle line:90%


00:44:06.870 --> 00:44:08.260 align:middle line:90%
The root test was--

00:44:08.260 --> 00:44:10.920 align:middle line:90%
so you're looking at the a n.

00:44:10.920 --> 00:44:13.710 align:middle line:84%
You take the-- so
this is the root test.

00:44:13.710 --> 00:44:17.760 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is
tested by comparing it

00:44:17.760 --> 00:44:19.840 align:middle line:90%
to the geometric series--

00:44:19.840 --> 00:44:22.410 align:middle line:90%
so the root test.

00:44:22.410 --> 00:44:29.420 align:middle line:84%
So you take the a n, take
the n-th root of this,

00:44:29.420 --> 00:44:31.760 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking
at the limit here.

00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:36.320 align:middle line:84%
And we actually
looked at the lim sup.

00:44:36.320 --> 00:44:38.510 align:middle line:90%
I'm writing the lim sup.

00:44:38.510 --> 00:44:45.110 align:middle line:84%
The reason why I want the lim
sup is that I want to make sure

00:44:45.110 --> 00:44:46.250 align:middle line:90%
that it's--

00:44:46.250 --> 00:44:49.020 align:middle line:84%
later on, I want to
apply more generally.

00:44:49.020 --> 00:44:52.170 align:middle line:90%


00:44:52.170 --> 00:44:58.070 align:middle line:84%
So if the lim sup
here was less than 1--

00:44:58.070 --> 00:45:02.000 align:middle line:84%
let's call the lim
sup-- let's call it c.

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:07.290 align:middle line:84%
If c here is less than 1,
then the series is convergent.

00:45:07.290 --> 00:45:12.230 align:middle line:90%


00:45:12.230 --> 00:45:16.940 align:middle line:84%
2-- if the c is bigger than
1, series is divergent.

00:45:16.940 --> 00:45:19.190 align:middle line:90%
This fails the most basic test--

00:45:19.190 --> 00:45:21.680 align:middle line:90%
divergent.

00:45:21.680 --> 00:45:26.580 align:middle line:84%
And again, 3-- if c is equal
to 1, then it's unclear.

00:45:26.580 --> 00:45:27.778 align:middle line:90%
Further tests are needed.

00:45:27.778 --> 00:45:32.590 align:middle line:90%


00:45:32.590 --> 00:45:35.020 align:middle line:90%
That was those two tests.

00:45:35.020 --> 00:45:38.420 align:middle line:84%
The comparison tests--
let's get back to that.

00:45:38.420 --> 00:45:43.690 align:middle line:84%
The comparison test has
two parts that you had.

00:45:43.690 --> 00:45:46.990 align:middle line:90%
Suppose you had a n and bn.

00:45:46.990 --> 00:45:49.420 align:middle line:84%
The first part is
this statement.

00:45:49.420 --> 00:45:52.390 align:middle line:84%
If you have two
series, one based

00:45:52.390 --> 00:45:55.550 align:middle line:84%
on the a n, another
series based on the bn--

00:45:55.550 --> 00:45:57.370 align:middle line:90%
if you have this--

00:45:57.370 --> 00:46:01.366 align:middle line:90%
if bn-- so this here--

00:46:01.366 --> 00:46:10.120 align:middle line:84%
if this series here is
convergent, then [INAUDIBLE]

00:46:10.120 --> 00:46:11.351 align:middle line:90%
is convergent.

00:46:11.351 --> 00:46:14.650 align:middle line:90%


00:46:14.650 --> 00:46:19.910 align:middle line:84%
And this is sometimes used
both exactly like this,

00:46:19.910 --> 00:46:22.840 align:middle line:84%
and it's also sometimes used
where you know that this one

00:46:22.840 --> 00:46:26.194 align:middle line:84%
here is divergent, and so
you compute that this one is

00:46:26.194 --> 00:46:31.220 align:middle line:84%
[? divergent. ?] The other
part of the comparison test was

00:46:31.220 --> 00:46:37.490 align:middle line:84%
if you had the limit here, if
this limit here exists and it

00:46:37.490 --> 00:46:43.800 align:middle line:84%
was something L, then
actually, it [? says ?] that--

00:46:43.800 --> 00:46:45.720 align:middle line:84%
let's say L here
is not equal to 0.

00:46:45.720 --> 00:46:50.951 align:middle line:90%


00:46:50.951 --> 00:46:56.730 align:middle line:84%
Then if one of
them is convergent,

00:46:56.730 --> 00:46:58.200 align:middle line:84%
the other one is
also convergent.

00:46:58.200 --> 00:47:01.290 align:middle line:90%
So if a n--

00:47:01.290 --> 00:47:06.490 align:middle line:84%
or bn, let's say--
bn is convergent,

00:47:06.490 --> 00:47:10.016 align:middle line:84%
then it implies that
a n is convergent.

00:47:10.016 --> 00:47:12.890 align:middle line:90%


00:47:12.890 --> 00:47:14.900 align:middle line:90%
And vice versa-- this actually--

00:47:14.900 --> 00:47:18.372 align:middle line:84%
[INAUDIBLE] this is
convergent [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:18.372 --> 00:47:21.110 align:middle line:90%


00:47:21.110 --> 00:47:24.800 align:middle line:84%
So those were the three tests
that we really went through.

00:47:24.800 --> 00:47:26.930 align:middle line:84%
There were a few other
tests, like, again,

00:47:26.930 --> 00:47:30.110 align:middle line:84%
this alternating series
test that we saw a proof,

00:47:30.110 --> 00:47:31.970 align:middle line:84%
but it's not going
to be on midterms,

00:47:31.970 --> 00:47:33.880 align:middle line:84%
and we will return
to this later.

00:47:33.880 --> 00:47:34.810 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:47:34.810 --> 00:47:37.120 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Are there
patterns of when

00:47:37.120 --> 00:47:39.020 align:middle line:90%
we should apply which tests?

00:47:39.020 --> 00:47:40.360 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah-- no.

00:47:40.360 --> 00:47:46.335 align:middle line:84%
And I want to get to
this in just a second.

00:47:46.335 --> 00:47:50.575 align:middle line:90%


00:47:50.575 --> 00:47:52.250 align:middle line:84%
Let me just say a
couple of words first,

00:47:52.250 --> 00:47:56.210 align:middle line:84%
and then let me jump to some
of the examples of problems,

00:47:56.210 --> 00:48:00.151 align:middle line:84%
and then I'll come back, and
then we'll do a little bit more.

00:48:00.151 --> 00:48:05.950 align:middle line:84%
But let's just talk about
power series, and maybe--

00:48:05.950 --> 00:48:10.090 align:middle line:84%
let me think [INAUDIBLE]
and whether--

00:48:10.090 --> 00:48:14.740 align:middle line:84%
just now when you were
asking the question--

00:48:14.740 --> 00:48:16.910 align:middle line:84%
no, let's just review
the power series.

00:48:16.910 --> 00:48:21.060 align:middle line:90%


00:48:21.060 --> 00:48:24.540 align:middle line:84%
So our power series
was a series,

00:48:24.540 --> 00:48:28.791 align:middle line:84%
but it was something that
also defined a function.

00:48:28.791 --> 00:48:30.930 align:middle line:90%
And so you take--

00:48:30.930 --> 00:48:40.805 align:middle line:90%
so you have-- so a power change.

00:48:40.805 --> 00:48:46.260 align:middle line:90%


00:48:46.260 --> 00:48:49.194 align:middle line:90%
So you have a sequence a n.

00:48:49.194 --> 00:48:51.540 align:middle line:90%
And then you think for each x--

00:48:51.540 --> 00:48:54.210 align:middle line:84%
for x, think about
x as being fixed--

00:48:54.210 --> 00:49:00.130 align:middle line:84%
you form a series, and this
is the series that you form.

00:49:00.130 --> 00:49:03.270 align:middle line:90%


00:49:03.270 --> 00:49:06.210 align:middle line:84%
And so for each
x you can ask, is

00:49:06.210 --> 00:49:08.910 align:middle line:90%
this series convergent or not?

00:49:08.910 --> 00:49:13.230 align:middle line:84%
This here is called
a power series.

00:49:13.230 --> 00:49:19.000 align:middle line:84%
And the key point for power
series is, again, of course,

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:21.640 align:middle line:84%
whether or not
this is convergent.

00:49:21.640 --> 00:49:25.310 align:middle line:84%
And this gave rise to the
radius of convergence.

00:49:25.310 --> 00:49:31.600 align:middle line:90%


00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:36.340 align:middle line:84%
And so the radius
of convergence was--

00:49:36.340 --> 00:49:48.220 align:middle line:84%
that we defined-- we looked at
lim sup of the n-th root of a n,

00:49:48.220 --> 00:49:50.630 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:49:50.630 --> 00:49:54.040 align:middle line:84%
And we looked at when
this thing here--

00:49:54.040 --> 00:49:57.910 align:middle line:90%
if this thing here is--

00:49:57.910 --> 00:50:03.760 align:middle line:84%
actually, we defined
this thing here, and--

00:50:03.760 --> 00:50:05.270 align:middle line:90%
so we got this thing here.

00:50:05.270 --> 00:50:07.670 align:middle line:84%
And then we defined the
radius of convergence.

00:50:07.670 --> 00:50:15.070 align:middle line:90%
So the radius of convergence--

00:50:15.070 --> 00:50:20.796 align:middle line:84%
this is R, and the R
is 1 over this lim sup.

00:50:20.796 --> 00:50:23.490 align:middle line:90%


00:50:23.490 --> 00:50:27.600 align:middle line:84%
But there was an
understanding in this.

00:50:27.600 --> 00:50:32.310 align:middle line:84%
The understanding is that
if this number here--

00:50:32.310 --> 00:50:36.930 align:middle line:84%
this number potentially
could be infinite.

00:50:36.930 --> 00:50:42.360 align:middle line:84%
If it was infinite, it meant
that this thing here was 0.

00:50:42.360 --> 00:50:46.590 align:middle line:90%
If this one here is infinity--

00:50:46.590 --> 00:50:54.018 align:middle line:84%
if this here is 0, then
this here would be infinity.

00:50:54.018 --> 00:50:57.690 align:middle line:84%
So that's like a convention
in this particular case.

00:50:57.690 --> 00:51:00.760 align:middle line:84%
Usually, we don't want to
divide by 0 [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:00.760 --> 00:51:05.370 align:middle line:84%
But this is a convention
in this particular case.

00:51:05.370 --> 00:51:08.280 align:middle line:84%
And so using this
radius of convergence,

00:51:08.280 --> 00:51:11.140 align:middle line:84%
we saw that if you
take a power series,

00:51:11.140 --> 00:51:15.200 align:middle line:84%
if you have any power
series like this--

00:51:15.200 --> 00:51:16.850 align:middle line:90%
here you have 0--

00:51:16.850 --> 00:51:20.940 align:middle line:84%
any power series like
this, it's going to be--

00:51:20.940 --> 00:51:23.510 align:middle line:90%
if this here is R--

00:51:23.510 --> 00:51:27.860 align:middle line:84%
and again, R could be 0
or it could be infinity.

00:51:27.860 --> 00:51:30.350 align:middle line:90%
But if this is R--

00:51:30.350 --> 00:51:33.170 align:middle line:84%
sorry, I should write
this with a minus sign.

00:51:33.170 --> 00:51:37.190 align:middle line:90%
Then for x in between--

00:51:37.190 --> 00:51:41.690 align:middle line:84%
for x not including the
endpoints, but in between--

00:51:41.690 --> 00:51:43.880 align:middle line:90%
the series is convergent.

00:51:43.880 --> 00:51:45.680 align:middle line:90%
The power series is convergent.

00:51:45.680 --> 00:51:49.740 align:middle line:84%
And outside here,
it's divergent.

00:51:49.740 --> 00:51:52.820 align:middle line:90%


00:51:52.820 --> 00:51:54.360 align:middle line:90%
Outside is divergent.

00:51:54.360 --> 00:51:55.742 align:middle line:90%
Here it's convergent.

00:51:55.742 --> 00:51:58.640 align:middle line:90%


00:51:58.640 --> 00:52:04.216 align:middle line:84%
And at those two
points here, unclear.

00:52:04.216 --> 00:52:06.750 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]

00:52:06.750 --> 00:52:08.840 align:middle line:90%
So this is always this picture.

00:52:08.840 --> 00:52:13.480 align:middle line:84%
So this comes back to your
question about which tests--

00:52:13.480 --> 00:52:15.550 align:middle line:84%
of course, you can
use any test you want,

00:52:15.550 --> 00:52:18.850 align:middle line:84%
but when I-- like if
you're looking at a series,

00:52:18.850 --> 00:52:20.830 align:middle line:84%
you can use whatever
test you want.

00:52:20.830 --> 00:52:23.850 align:middle line:84%
But if it was a power
series, you already

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:31.240 align:middle line:84%
know that there's some interval
around 0 where it's convergent,

00:52:31.240 --> 00:52:33.730 align:middle line:84%
and then there's a question
about the endpoints.

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:41.555 align:middle line:84%
And so now let's look at
some examples of this.

00:52:41.555 --> 00:52:44.100 align:middle line:90%


00:52:44.100 --> 00:52:47.500 align:middle line:90%
And suppose you look at--

00:52:47.500 --> 00:52:59.280 align:middle line:84%
and so It's usually not
too hard to use either--

00:52:59.280 --> 00:53:02.670 align:middle line:90%


00:53:02.670 --> 00:53:05.160 align:middle line:84%
this here was based
on the root test,

00:53:05.160 --> 00:53:08.290 align:middle line:84%
so you use the root test
or the ratio test for power

00:53:08.290 --> 00:53:12.260 align:middle line:84%
[? convergence. ?] But you can
take advantage of it sometimes

00:53:12.260 --> 00:53:14.130 align:middle line:90%
it's just slightly easier.

00:53:14.130 --> 00:53:16.310 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at
two examples here.

00:53:16.310 --> 00:53:32.420 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that you're asked to
find the radius of convergence

00:53:32.420 --> 00:53:33.540 align:middle line:90%
for the power series.

00:53:33.540 --> 00:53:40.250 align:middle line:90%


00:53:40.250 --> 00:53:45.920 align:middle line:84%
And then let's say that this
is n to the fifth power, xn.

00:53:45.920 --> 00:53:50.840 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that you are-- this
is a power series you're given,

00:53:50.840 --> 00:53:55.710 align:middle line:84%
and you want to find the
radius of convergence.

00:53:55.710 --> 00:54:03.950 align:middle line:84%
You can either just
plug it into this test,

00:54:03.950 --> 00:54:06.750 align:middle line:84%
or you can just say,
OK, we'll just apply it.

00:54:06.750 --> 00:54:09.240 align:middle line:84%
We know that it's some
interval, and I just

00:54:09.240 --> 00:54:12.570 align:middle line:84%
want to see for which x
does this here converge.

00:54:12.570 --> 00:54:14.790 align:middle line:84%
So if I looked--
in this case, you

00:54:14.790 --> 00:54:20.160 align:middle line:84%
might find it slightly
easier to do the root test.

00:54:20.160 --> 00:54:23.780 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking at the n
plus 1 element in this series--

00:54:23.780 --> 00:54:26.730 align:middle line:90%


00:54:26.730 --> 00:54:29.900 align:middle line:84%
n elements would be
this to the fifth power.

00:54:29.900 --> 00:54:34.470 align:middle line:84%
Think about x as being fixed,
and you're asking for which x.

00:54:34.470 --> 00:54:36.600 align:middle line:84%
And then you want
to-- for a given x,

00:54:36.600 --> 00:54:39.190 align:middle line:84%
you want to determine
whether the series--

00:54:39.190 --> 00:54:44.310 align:middle line:84%
this series here--
is convergent.

00:54:44.310 --> 00:54:46.980 align:middle line:84%
So if you were
using the root test,

00:54:46.980 --> 00:54:48.720 align:middle line:84%
you would look at
this thing here.

00:54:48.720 --> 00:54:51.120 align:middle line:84%
And you might find in
this case slightly easier

00:54:51.120 --> 00:54:53.610 align:middle line:90%
to use the root test.

00:54:53.610 --> 00:54:56.340 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking
at this, this thing

00:54:56.340 --> 00:55:02.820 align:middle line:84%
here is now n plus 1 to the
fifth power times x to the n

00:55:02.820 --> 00:55:10.100 align:middle line:84%
plus 1 divided by n to the
fifth power times x to the n.

00:55:10.100 --> 00:55:12.230 align:middle line:90%
That's that ratio.

00:55:12.230 --> 00:55:15.380 align:middle line:84%
And so of course, you
can write this here.

00:55:15.380 --> 00:55:22.520 align:middle line:84%
This is like-- sorry, n plus 1
multiplied by itself five times,

00:55:22.520 --> 00:55:27.350 align:middle line:84%
divided by n multiplied
by itself five times.

00:55:27.350 --> 00:55:31.070 align:middle line:84%
And then this thing here-- you
can write it as x to the n,

00:55:31.070 --> 00:55:36.980 align:middle line:90%
times x, over x to the n.

00:55:36.980 --> 00:55:41.180 align:middle line:84%
So you see, this thing here,
you can then think about as n

00:55:41.180 --> 00:55:54.030 align:middle line:84%
plus 1 over n to the
fifth power, and times x.

00:55:54.030 --> 00:55:58.160 align:middle line:84%
And I can write this thing
here in the usual way.

00:55:58.160 --> 00:56:02.760 align:middle line:84%
If you want, you can
write it as 1 plus 1/n.

00:56:02.760 --> 00:56:04.940 align:middle line:84%
I'm dividing by n
in both denominator.

00:56:04.940 --> 00:56:07.330 align:middle line:84%
And denominator, you
can write it like this--

00:56:07.330 --> 00:56:12.040 align:middle line:90%
to the fifth power times x.

00:56:12.040 --> 00:56:15.325 align:middle line:90%
And so now-- the root test--

00:56:15.325 --> 00:56:17.870 align:middle line:90%


00:56:17.870 --> 00:56:19.540 align:middle line:90%
it's asking whether this--

00:56:19.540 --> 00:56:22.450 align:middle line:84%
the absolute value
of this root test

00:56:22.450 --> 00:56:29.080 align:middle line:84%
would be then asking if the
limit here of x n plus 1 over--

00:56:29.080 --> 00:56:32.020 align:middle line:90%
I'm sorry, a n plus 1 over a n--

00:56:32.020 --> 00:56:34.480 align:middle line:90%
if this here has a limit.

00:56:34.480 --> 00:56:39.200 align:middle line:84%
And then it's asking you, if
that limit is less than 1,

00:56:39.200 --> 00:56:41.360 align:middle line:84%
if it has a limit and
the limit is less than 1,

00:56:41.360 --> 00:56:43.640 align:middle line:84%
then the series is
convergent, and it's divergent

00:56:43.640 --> 00:56:44.890 align:middle line:90%
if it's bigger than 1.

00:56:44.890 --> 00:56:50.950 align:middle line:84%
But in this case, this
thing here, this ratio here,

00:56:50.950 --> 00:56:57.970 align:middle line:84%
is 1 plus 1/n to the
fifth power, times x.

00:56:57.970 --> 00:57:00.550 align:middle line:84%
But this is all non-negative,
so the absolute value is just

00:57:00.550 --> 00:57:01.620 align:middle line:90%
going over here.

00:57:01.620 --> 00:57:05.090 align:middle line:90%


00:57:05.090 --> 00:57:06.960 align:middle line:84%
The algebraic
property of the limit

00:57:06.960 --> 00:57:10.790 align:middle line:84%
says that this one
here goes to 0,

00:57:10.790 --> 00:57:13.920 align:middle line:84%
and so raised to the fifth
power still goes to 0.

00:57:13.920 --> 00:57:18.120 align:middle line:84%
It's multiplying a bunch of
sequences five times together.

00:57:18.120 --> 00:57:18.890 align:middle line:90%
That gives you 0.

00:57:18.890 --> 00:57:22.700 align:middle line:84%
To 1, [? too-- ?] so
this here this goes to 1,

00:57:22.700 --> 00:57:25.230 align:middle line:84%
and so even raised to the
fifth power, still goes to 1.

00:57:25.230 --> 00:57:29.720 align:middle line:84%
So this here goes
to the norm of x.

00:57:29.720 --> 00:57:33.920 align:middle line:84%
And so the ratio test
would be that if x here--

00:57:33.920 --> 00:57:35.540 align:middle line:90%
so the ratio test gives you--

00:57:35.540 --> 00:57:39.244 align:middle line:90%


00:57:39.244 --> 00:57:42.530 align:middle line:84%
is that if this norm
here is less than 1, then

00:57:42.530 --> 00:57:45.380 align:middle line:90%
this series is convergent.

00:57:45.380 --> 00:57:51.620 align:middle line:84%
If the norm here is bigger
than 1, the ratio is divergent.

00:57:51.620 --> 00:57:55.230 align:middle line:84%
And it's unclear if
the norm is equal to 1.

00:57:55.230 --> 00:57:58.520 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, you see
that the ratio test here

00:57:58.520 --> 00:58:02.520 align:middle line:84%
gives you directly that the
radius of convergence is 1.

00:58:02.520 --> 00:58:05.026 align:middle line:90%


00:58:05.026 --> 00:58:10.312 align:middle line:84%
And of course, you could
apply the root test.

00:58:10.312 --> 00:58:13.920 align:middle line:84%
The root test is
great on this here.

00:58:13.920 --> 00:58:15.550 align:middle line:90%
It's a little bit more--

00:58:15.550 --> 00:58:17.618 align:middle line:84%
no, you have to do a
little bit more argument.

00:58:17.618 --> 00:58:18.410 align:middle line:90%
It's not very hard.

00:58:18.410 --> 00:58:21.520 align:middle line:84%
But it actually-- in
this case, the ratio test

00:58:21.520 --> 00:58:24.070 align:middle line:84%
would be easier to--
it would be less

00:58:24.070 --> 00:58:27.580 align:middle line:90%
to argue than in the root test.

00:58:27.580 --> 00:58:31.360 align:middle line:84%
Let's do one more
example of this.

00:58:31.360 --> 00:58:34.360 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I'll just switch
a little bit [? to-- ?]

00:58:34.360 --> 00:58:39.130 align:middle line:84%
and then I'll come back
and review some more stuff.

00:58:39.130 --> 00:58:41.410 align:middle line:84%
I'll just talk about
a few of the problems

00:58:41.410 --> 00:58:45.140 align:middle line:84%
that I added to the
end of my review notes.

00:58:45.140 --> 00:58:49.375 align:middle line:84%
Again, I'll post this
with these problems.

00:58:49.375 --> 00:58:52.040 align:middle line:90%
And obviously, they are--

00:58:52.040 --> 00:58:54.730 align:middle line:84%
it's not exactly
problems on the midterm,

00:58:54.730 --> 00:58:57.190 align:middle line:84%
but [INAUDIBLE] it's certainly
relevant to the midterm.

00:58:57.190 --> 00:59:06.274 align:middle line:90%


00:59:06.274 --> 00:59:07.890 align:middle line:84%
And also, another
thing I want to say

00:59:07.890 --> 00:59:15.930 align:middle line:84%
is that the homework is
graded up to and including 4.

00:59:15.930 --> 00:59:18.580 align:middle line:84%
So I wasn't actually aware
of, over the weekend,

00:59:18.580 --> 00:59:20.640 align:middle line:84%
they were supposed to
be handed back within,

00:59:20.640 --> 00:59:23.770 align:middle line:84%
latest, a week of
when you handed it in,

00:59:23.770 --> 00:59:28.320 align:middle line:84%
and I just discovered it over
the weekend that it was--

00:59:28.320 --> 00:59:33.840 align:middle line:84%
some of them were late,
so-- but it's fixed.

00:59:33.840 --> 00:59:35.400 align:middle line:90%
I'm not the grader.

00:59:35.400 --> 00:59:40.650 align:middle line:84%
There's two [INAUDIBLE] that
are grading and a grader.

00:59:40.650 --> 00:59:42.130 align:middle line:90%
But it's all fixed now.

00:59:42.130 --> 00:59:45.400 align:middle line:90%
So the first four are--

00:59:45.400 --> 00:59:51.150 align:middle line:84%
you can review those
also for the midterm.

00:59:51.150 --> 00:59:58.450 align:middle line:84%
So the other power series
I want to look at is--

00:59:58.450 --> 01:00:01.839 align:middle line:84%
so again, what is the
radius of convergence?

01:00:01.839 --> 01:00:09.530 align:middle line:90%


01:00:09.530 --> 01:00:11.200 align:middle line:84%
The nice thing
about power series

01:00:11.200 --> 01:00:16.210 align:middle line:84%
is that power series
also test about series.

01:00:16.210 --> 01:00:16.960 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE]

01:00:16.960 --> 01:00:21.730 align:middle line:90%


01:00:21.730 --> 01:00:28.900 align:middle line:84%
So what is the radius
of convergence for--

01:00:28.900 --> 01:00:32.650 align:middle line:84%
and now the series is a
slightly different series.

01:00:32.650 --> 01:00:33.890 align:middle line:90%
It's this series here--

01:00:33.890 --> 01:00:38.950 align:middle line:90%


01:00:38.950 --> 01:00:40.010 align:middle line:90%
so this series.

01:00:40.010 --> 01:00:42.895 align:middle line:90%


01:00:42.895 --> 01:00:45.010 align:middle line:90%
And so now let me--

01:00:45.010 --> 01:00:48.050 align:middle line:84%
again, you could
apply the root test.

01:00:48.050 --> 01:00:52.970 align:middle line:84%
The root test is the one that
just gives you an answer.

01:00:52.970 --> 01:00:56.070 align:middle line:84%
It always gives you
an answer, but you

01:00:56.070 --> 01:01:01.610 align:middle line:84%
may have to work harder
to find the n-th root,

01:01:01.610 --> 01:01:04.690 align:middle line:84%
and sometimes it's just
easier to use the ratio test.

01:01:04.690 --> 01:01:07.210 align:middle line:84%
So let's use the
ratio test again.

01:01:07.210 --> 01:01:12.060 align:middle line:84%
So a n here is n to the
fifth power, x to the n,

01:01:12.060 --> 01:01:13.800 align:middle line:90%
over n factorial.

01:01:13.800 --> 01:01:19.887 align:middle line:84%
So if you're looking at a n plus
1 over a n-- maybe I should--

01:01:19.887 --> 01:01:21.220 align:middle line:90%
maybe let me write it over here.

01:01:21.220 --> 01:01:27.180 align:middle line:90%


01:01:27.180 --> 01:01:33.040 align:middle line:84%
So if I'm looking at
a n plus 1 over a n--

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:36.840 align:middle line:90%


01:01:36.840 --> 01:01:44.220 align:middle line:84%
so then I have the n plus
1 to the fifth power, times

01:01:44.220 --> 01:01:55.740 align:middle line:84%
x to the power n plus 1,
over n plus 1 factorial.

01:01:55.740 --> 01:01:57.590 align:middle line:90%
That is a n plus 1.

01:01:57.590 --> 01:02:00.060 align:middle line:84%
And then I have
to divide by this,

01:02:00.060 --> 01:02:02.300 align:middle line:84%
but when I divide
by a fraction, it's

01:02:02.300 --> 01:02:06.990 align:middle line:84%
like multiplying by
the inverse of this.

01:02:06.990 --> 01:02:09.470 align:middle line:90%
So like this thing here--

01:02:09.470 --> 01:02:15.260 align:middle line:84%
[INAUDIBLE] the n power,
x to the n power--

01:02:15.260 --> 01:02:17.540 align:middle line:90%
like that.

01:02:17.540 --> 01:02:27.110 align:middle line:84%
And so again, [INAUDIBLE] I
can write this thing here as--

01:02:27.110 --> 01:02:30.300 align:middle line:84%
so if I just do
like I did before,

01:02:30.300 --> 01:02:36.270 align:middle line:84%
I would have that n plus 1
over n, to the fifth power.

01:02:36.270 --> 01:02:40.730 align:middle line:84%
That's when I take this one
here and that one together.

01:02:40.730 --> 01:02:43.710 align:middle line:84%
Then I have-- when I
take those two together,

01:02:43.710 --> 01:02:49.070 align:middle line:84%
I can get rid of the n
here, and I just get an x.

01:02:49.070 --> 01:02:53.700 align:middle line:84%
And then when I look at
the ratio of these two,

01:02:53.700 --> 01:02:55.470 align:middle line:90%
this one here--

01:02:55.470 --> 01:02:58.260 align:middle line:90%
n plus 1 factorial--

01:02:58.260 --> 01:03:01.200 align:middle line:84%
you can think about
that as n plus 1

01:03:01.200 --> 01:03:03.360 align:middle line:90%
and then times n factorial.

01:03:03.360 --> 01:03:08.080 align:middle line:84%
And so this n factorial
cancel out with that,

01:03:08.080 --> 01:03:10.680 align:middle line:84%
and you're left
with an n plus 1.

01:03:10.680 --> 01:03:14.430 align:middle line:90%
So this is what you get.

01:03:14.430 --> 01:03:16.120 align:middle line:90%
And this one here--

01:03:16.120 --> 01:03:18.580 align:middle line:84%
just writing it
as we did before,

01:03:18.580 --> 01:03:26.550 align:middle line:84%
dividing this fraction by 1/n in
both numerator and denominator,

01:03:26.550 --> 01:03:33.720 align:middle line:84%
getting this thing here to the
power of 5 times x n plus 1.

01:03:33.720 --> 01:03:36.180 align:middle line:90%
And now you see that--

01:03:36.180 --> 01:03:38.430 align:middle line:84%
and this here, I
guess it should have

01:03:38.430 --> 01:03:40.350 align:middle line:84%
been absolute value
[? applied, ?]

01:03:40.350 --> 01:03:47.670 align:middle line:84%
so it's absolute value
on this, like that.

01:03:47.670 --> 01:03:51.110 align:middle line:90%
This one here converged to 1.

01:03:51.110 --> 01:03:54.680 align:middle line:84%
This one is just x, so
this converged to x.

01:03:54.680 --> 01:03:57.270 align:middle line:84%
And then this here
goes to infinity,

01:03:57.270 --> 01:04:00.180 align:middle line:90%
so the ratio here goes to 0.

01:04:00.180 --> 01:04:03.380 align:middle line:84%
I'm using the algebraic
property of limits.

01:04:03.380 --> 01:04:06.590 align:middle line:90%
So this is converging to 0.

01:04:06.590 --> 01:04:11.810 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that it does
have a limit, so the ratio test

01:04:11.810 --> 01:04:16.400 align:middle line:84%
[? applied ?] because
that limit is 0 for all x,

01:04:16.400 --> 01:04:18.480 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be
convergent for all x.

01:04:18.480 --> 01:04:21.130 align:middle line:84%
So the radius of
convergence in this case--

01:04:21.130 --> 01:04:29.960 align:middle line:90%


01:04:29.960 --> 01:04:33.620 align:middle line:84%
and of course, on the
midterm, don't just

01:04:33.620 --> 01:04:36.560 align:middle line:84%
say that the radius of
convergence is infinite.

01:04:36.560 --> 01:04:39.660 align:middle line:84%
Explain this thing here,
and the more detail,

01:04:39.660 --> 01:04:43.940 align:middle line:84%
the better, because even
if there's some typos,

01:04:43.940 --> 01:04:46.650 align:middle line:84%
you definitely get
should definitely get--

01:04:46.650 --> 01:04:48.130 align:middle line:84%
I'm not grading
the midterm either,

01:04:48.130 --> 01:04:50.400 align:middle line:84%
but you definitely should
get partial credit.

01:04:50.400 --> 01:04:51.390 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:04:51.390 --> 01:04:53.370 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So to
get R, is it always

01:04:53.370 --> 01:04:55.150 align:middle line:90%
like you divide by the lim sup?

01:04:55.150 --> 01:04:57.360 align:middle line:84%
Because-- is the thing
on the bottom one

01:04:57.360 --> 01:04:58.810 align:middle line:90%
the lim sup or just the lim?

01:04:58.810 --> 01:04:59.685 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

01:04:59.685 --> 01:05:02.580 align:middle line:90%


01:05:02.580 --> 01:05:11.361 align:middle line:84%
So when you take just a
complete general series,

01:05:11.361 --> 01:05:15.300 align:middle line:84%
then the radius of convergence
is by definition this.

01:05:15.300 --> 01:05:16.785 align:middle line:90%
This is related to--

01:05:16.785 --> 01:05:19.830 align:middle line:84%
you asked this question a
couple of times ago that--

01:05:19.830 --> 01:05:22.530 align:middle line:84%
because we started
with the ratio test.

01:05:22.530 --> 01:05:24.480 align:middle line:84%
We did that before
we did the root test.

01:05:24.480 --> 01:05:27.390 align:middle line:84%
And you were noting
that in the ratio test,

01:05:27.390 --> 01:05:32.610 align:middle line:84%
you're always comparing an
element to the previous one.

01:05:32.610 --> 01:05:35.700 align:middle line:84%
And in general, the
series can be convergent

01:05:35.700 --> 01:05:38.160 align:middle line:84%
even though the next
element is slightly

01:05:38.160 --> 01:05:40.020 align:middle line:90%
larger than the previous.

01:05:40.020 --> 01:05:43.090 align:middle line:84%
If that keeps happening,
it's not convergent,

01:05:43.090 --> 01:05:47.140 align:middle line:84%
but it could happen a few times,
and then it goes really down,

01:05:47.140 --> 01:05:48.680 align:middle line:90%
and that's fine.

01:05:48.680 --> 01:05:54.370 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why I
like the root test--

01:05:54.370 --> 01:05:59.020 align:middle line:84%
gives you this general result
about that it's always--

01:05:59.020 --> 01:05:59.890 align:middle line:90%
it always works.

01:05:59.890 --> 01:06:05.220 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't assume that the
a n's are not 0, et cetera.

01:06:05.220 --> 01:06:07.950 align:middle line:84%
For any particular--
and it really

01:06:07.950 --> 01:06:09.760 align:middle line:90%
should be the lim sup here.

01:06:09.760 --> 01:06:11.835 align:middle line:90%
And then it's defined.

01:06:11.835 --> 01:06:13.565 align:middle line:84%
It's a number that's
always defined.

01:06:13.565 --> 01:06:16.760 align:middle line:90%


01:06:16.760 --> 01:06:20.640 align:middle line:84%
And again, the way it's stated
here, the way the proof goes,

01:06:20.640 --> 01:06:26.290 align:middle line:84%
is it's not comparing
two consecutive a n.

01:06:26.290 --> 01:06:28.860 align:middle line:90%


01:06:28.860 --> 01:06:32.310 align:middle line:84%
In any particular
example, the root test

01:06:32.310 --> 01:06:35.850 align:middle line:84%
may not be the
easiest way to argue.

01:06:35.850 --> 01:06:40.500 align:middle line:84%
Often, if you can,
for a power series--

01:06:40.500 --> 01:06:45.940 align:middle line:84%
almost always, I would
say, in a power series,

01:06:45.940 --> 01:06:51.050 align:middle line:84%
it's almost always easier
to use the ratio test,

01:06:51.050 --> 01:06:56.770 align:middle line:84%
but it requires that the power
series has some nice property

01:06:56.770 --> 01:06:58.180 align:middle line:90%
for this to apply.

01:06:58.180 --> 01:06:59.540 align:middle line:90%
[INAUDIBLE] Yeah?

01:06:59.540 --> 01:07:01.915 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So [INAUDIBLE] R
is infinity for that example,

01:07:01.915 --> 01:07:04.540 align:middle line:84%
it was because it was convergent
for all x [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:04.540 --> 01:07:07.200 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So in
this example here--

01:07:07.200 --> 01:07:10.130 align:middle line:84%
then yeah, this
here is infinity,

01:07:10.130 --> 01:07:13.750 align:middle line:84%
which means that this
thing here would be 0.

01:07:13.750 --> 01:07:15.310 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:07:15.310 --> 01:07:16.800 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: But you
know [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:16.800 --> 01:07:18.800 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: But I
didn't actually calculate.

01:07:18.800 --> 01:07:21.820 align:middle line:84%
You see, I didn't calculate the
[INAUDIBLE] in this example.

01:07:21.820 --> 01:07:24.920 align:middle line:84%
But if I had calculated,
I would actually--

01:07:24.920 --> 01:07:26.420 align:middle line:84%
and it's not very
hard to calculate,

01:07:26.420 --> 01:07:29.140 align:middle line:84%
but it needs some
small tricks, and so--

01:07:29.140 --> 01:07:31.720 align:middle line:84%
and we haven't-- yeah,
we haven't talked about.

01:07:31.720 --> 01:07:34.240 align:middle line:90%


01:07:34.240 --> 01:07:37.210 align:middle line:90%
So that's why I [INAUDIBLE].

01:07:37.210 --> 01:07:41.760 align:middle line:84%
Let me talk about a few
other things, and then--

01:07:41.760 --> 01:07:48.310 align:middle line:84%
so again, I don't think I
can [INAUDIBLE] review all

01:07:48.310 --> 01:07:51.740 align:middle line:90%
what I had in my review notes.

01:07:51.740 --> 01:07:54.900 align:middle line:84%
But let me just talk about a
few of the problems that I had.

01:07:54.900 --> 01:07:58.440 align:middle line:84%
But again-- so the
things I want--

01:07:58.440 --> 01:08:01.730 align:middle line:84%
let me just quickly mention
the things I may or may not

01:08:01.730 --> 01:08:05.600 align:middle line:84%
get to that I have
in my review notes.

01:08:05.600 --> 01:08:10.940 align:middle line:84%
So I had also
[INAUDIBLE] property--

01:08:10.940 --> 01:08:12.350 align:middle line:90%
what is lim sup?

01:08:12.350 --> 01:08:13.590 align:middle line:90%
What is lim inf?

01:08:13.590 --> 01:08:17.750 align:middle line:84%
And so definitely
review that also.

01:08:17.750 --> 01:08:21.350 align:middle line:84%
Talked about the
radius of convergence.

01:08:21.350 --> 01:08:23.660 align:middle line:84%
Well, maybe this is
all, and then talk

01:08:23.660 --> 01:08:25.910 align:middle line:84%
a little bit about
the power series

01:08:25.910 --> 01:08:28.109 align:middle line:90%
for the exponential functions.

01:08:28.109 --> 01:08:32.840 align:middle line:84%
But again, all the stuff
we did on the power series

01:08:32.840 --> 01:08:36.319 align:middle line:90%
for the exponential functions--

01:08:36.319 --> 01:08:39.279 align:middle line:84%
at this point, we
have established this.

01:08:39.279 --> 01:08:44.029 align:middle line:90%
This is like-- it's more like--

01:08:44.029 --> 01:08:46.729 align:middle line:84%
there won't be anything
particular about them.

01:08:46.729 --> 01:08:50.359 align:middle line:84%
The exponential function
itself could be on the midterm,

01:08:50.359 --> 01:08:54.279 align:middle line:84%
but it's not like you would
have to prove the properties

01:08:54.279 --> 01:08:56.029 align:middle line:90%
of the exponential function.

01:08:56.029 --> 01:08:58.569 align:middle line:84%
This property-- that
it has the property

01:08:58.569 --> 01:09:01.779 align:middle line:84%
that the exponential
function of x plus y

01:09:01.779 --> 01:09:05.420 align:middle line:84%
is the product of that kind of
stuff-- it's not on the midterm.

01:09:05.420 --> 01:09:09.069 align:middle line:84%
So I didn't-- so it's
not part of the review.

01:09:09.069 --> 01:09:12.430 align:middle line:84%
The other thing that I
probably won't get to,

01:09:12.430 --> 01:09:15.050 align:middle line:84%
because in a minute I'll just
turn to these other problems,

01:09:15.050 --> 01:09:16.840 align:middle line:90%
is that metric spaces--

01:09:16.840 --> 01:09:19.180 align:middle line:90%
definitely review metric spaces.

01:09:19.180 --> 01:09:20.800 align:middle line:90%
It was in the last lecture.

01:09:20.800 --> 01:09:23.214 align:middle line:90%
So there's a bunch of--

01:09:23.214 --> 01:09:25.910 align:middle line:84%
there's three properties
for a metric space.

01:09:25.910 --> 01:09:27.649 align:middle line:84%
The distance should
be non-negative,

01:09:27.649 --> 01:09:30.880 align:middle line:84%
it should be symmetric, and
the distance between two points

01:09:30.880 --> 01:09:33.470 align:middle line:84%
should be 0 if and only if
those points are the same.

01:09:33.470 --> 01:09:37.750 align:middle line:84%
And then the crucial property
in the metric space--

01:09:37.750 --> 01:09:40.229 align:middle line:84%
then that's like the
powerful property--

01:09:40.229 --> 01:09:43.630 align:middle line:90%
is the triangle inequality.

01:09:43.630 --> 01:09:46.020 align:middle line:90%
And so there was a few examples.

01:09:46.020 --> 01:09:48.330 align:middle line:90%
And review those examples.

01:09:48.330 --> 01:09:50.399 align:middle line:90%
They are in my review notes.

01:09:50.399 --> 01:09:53.790 align:middle line:84%
The most important
example, I would say, is--

01:09:53.790 --> 01:09:59.050 align:middle line:84%
the French rail metric is
kind of a crazy metric.

01:09:59.050 --> 01:10:00.940 align:middle line:84%
That's not one of
the important ones.

01:10:00.940 --> 01:10:05.010 align:middle line:84%
So I just did review notes as
just the most important ones.

01:10:05.010 --> 01:10:06.720 align:middle line:84%
And then there's
this with, what does

01:10:06.720 --> 01:10:09.220 align:middle line:84%
it mean to be convergent
in a metric space,

01:10:09.220 --> 01:10:12.930 align:middle line:84%
and what does it mean
to be a Cauchy sequence?

01:10:12.930 --> 01:10:18.120 align:middle line:84%
And so now let's get to a
couple of the other problems

01:10:18.120 --> 01:10:21.690 align:middle line:84%
that I suggested
that you look at.

01:10:21.690 --> 01:10:28.080 align:middle line:84%
And so here are
two other problems.

01:10:28.080 --> 01:10:30.720 align:middle line:84%
And again, I won't
get to-- there's also

01:10:30.720 --> 01:10:33.060 align:middle line:84%
problems about metric spaces,
and you should definitely

01:10:33.060 --> 01:10:35.310 align:middle line:84%
look at it, but I
don't have the time

01:10:35.310 --> 01:10:39.430 align:middle line:84%
now, even though it's
relevant for the midterm.

01:10:39.430 --> 01:10:40.620 align:middle line:90%
I just have to pick some.

01:10:40.620 --> 01:10:44.440 align:middle line:90%


01:10:44.440 --> 01:10:46.690 align:middle line:84%
Again, all of the
problems that I--

01:10:46.690 --> 01:10:48.590 align:middle line:90%
I have four problems here.

01:10:48.590 --> 01:10:51.340 align:middle line:84%
All of these are
relevant for the midterm.

01:10:51.340 --> 01:10:56.840 align:middle line:84%
So now-- suppose
you take a sequence.

01:10:56.840 --> 01:10:59.440 align:middle line:90%
So I have a sequence here, xn.

01:10:59.440 --> 01:11:03.790 align:middle line:84%
And so often, a sequence
is defined recursively.

01:11:03.790 --> 01:11:18.520 align:middle line:84%
So recursive-- so recursively
defined [INAUDIBLE] sequences.

01:11:18.520 --> 01:11:20.090 align:middle line:90%
So what does it mean?

01:11:20.090 --> 01:11:22.270 align:middle line:84%
It means that
typically, you have--

01:11:22.270 --> 01:11:25.330 align:middle line:84%
the first one is
defined to be whatever,

01:11:25.330 --> 01:11:29.680 align:middle line:84%
and then the next one is
defined from the previous one.

01:11:29.680 --> 01:11:34.230 align:middle line:84%
And so the one I was
suggesting looking at here

01:11:34.230 --> 01:11:44.535 align:middle line:84%
is that-- you see this here,
the first one [INAUDIBLE].

01:11:44.535 --> 01:11:45.910 align:middle line:84%
And then-- actually,
[INAUDIBLE].

01:11:45.910 --> 01:11:48.255 align:middle line:84%
And then the next one-- let
me just do this one here.

01:11:48.255 --> 01:11:50.380 align:middle line:84%
It's actually simpler than
what I have in my notes,

01:11:50.380 --> 01:11:53.400 align:middle line:84%
but maybe that one,
but I just want to--

01:11:53.400 --> 01:12:00.180 align:middle line:84%
so the next one is
defined to be xn over n.

01:12:00.180 --> 01:12:08.310 align:middle line:84%
And so then-- so
now, the question

01:12:08.310 --> 01:12:27.452 align:middle line:84%
would be, for what a does this
have a limit-- the sequence have

01:12:27.452 --> 01:12:30.450 align:middle line:90%
a limit.

01:12:30.450 --> 01:12:32.630 align:middle line:84%
And so you see
that in this case--

01:12:32.630 --> 01:12:35.060 align:middle line:84%
we only have four minutes
left, so I want to [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:35.060 --> 01:12:37.190 align:middle line:90%
But this is also--

01:12:37.190 --> 01:12:40.840 align:middle line:84%
I just wanted you to review
what it means for a sequence

01:12:40.840 --> 01:12:44.360 align:middle line:90%
to be defined recursively.

01:12:44.360 --> 01:12:47.950 align:middle line:84%
And so you see
that in this case,

01:12:47.950 --> 01:12:50.860 align:middle line:90%
you have that this thing here--

01:12:50.860 --> 01:12:52.340 align:middle line:90%
it is going down.

01:12:52.340 --> 01:12:54.250 align:middle line:90%
It's actually going down.

01:12:54.250 --> 01:12:57.080 align:middle line:84%
It even could go
down by a fraction.

01:12:57.080 --> 01:13:00.610 align:middle line:84%
But now, it's like-- if you're
looking at this in here,

01:13:00.610 --> 01:13:05.200 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at xn, this here
is definitely going to converge,

01:13:05.200 --> 01:13:07.750 align:middle line:90%
whatever you start with.

01:13:07.750 --> 01:13:16.630 align:middle line:84%
So I claim that you will always
get that xn here converges to 0.

01:13:16.630 --> 01:13:20.650 align:middle line:84%
And it's just-- you see that if
you-- when you have something

01:13:20.650 --> 01:13:25.810 align:middle line:84%
recursively, it often
can pay to just write out

01:13:25.810 --> 01:13:27.410 align:middle line:90%
the first few terms.

01:13:27.410 --> 01:13:29.250 align:middle line:90%
So you have [? x1, ?] a.

01:13:29.250 --> 01:13:32.535 align:middle line:90%
x2 is equal to a.

01:13:32.535 --> 01:13:36.300 align:middle line:90%


01:13:36.300 --> 01:13:37.620 align:middle line:90%
It's also a.

01:13:37.620 --> 01:13:45.224 align:middle line:84%
But the previous one,
[? x3 ?] is now a/2.

01:13:45.224 --> 01:13:58.270 align:middle line:84%
x4 is then a/2, divided by
3, so this is a/6, and so on.

01:13:58.270 --> 01:14:00.100 align:middle line:84%
And so if you
continue like this,

01:14:00.100 --> 01:14:02.415 align:middle line:84%
you will see that
they get-- that it's

01:14:02.415 --> 01:14:05.970 align:middle line:84%
like a divided by some
larger and larger number.

01:14:05.970 --> 01:14:10.070 align:middle line:84%
But you have to, of course,
write it nicely out as a proof.

01:14:10.070 --> 01:14:13.380 align:middle line:90%
But this is proving that.

01:14:13.380 --> 01:14:16.450 align:middle line:84%
But again, this here-- if
you just did what I did,

01:14:16.450 --> 01:14:18.660 align:middle line:84%
that would not be enough
to get full credit,

01:14:18.660 --> 01:14:20.590 align:middle line:90%
so definitely write out.

01:14:20.590 --> 01:14:23.470 align:middle line:84%
The other thing, in
the last minutes here--

01:14:23.470 --> 01:14:32.340 align:middle line:84%
the other thing-- the other
example here [INAUDIBLE],

01:14:32.340 --> 01:14:35.250 align:middle line:84%
suppose you take a
series like this,

01:14:35.250 --> 01:14:40.580 align:middle line:84%
and suppose that a n here is
less than 1 over n squared.

01:14:40.580 --> 01:14:45.530 align:middle line:84%
And then the
question could be, is

01:14:45.530 --> 01:14:48.920 align:middle line:84%
the series-- suppose you knew
this, but that's all you know.

01:14:48.920 --> 01:14:58.140 align:middle line:84%
Is the series
convergent or divergent?

01:14:58.140 --> 01:15:03.380 align:middle line:90%


01:15:03.380 --> 01:15:07.140 align:middle line:84%
And then I say in
the notes here--

01:15:07.140 --> 01:15:09.770 align:middle line:90%
I mean, in the review here--

01:15:09.770 --> 01:15:14.780 align:middle line:84%
that either you should prove
that for all such series,

01:15:14.780 --> 01:15:18.060 align:middle line:84%
it's convergent, or if
that's not the case,

01:15:18.060 --> 01:15:20.630 align:middle line:84%
you should give an
example of a series

01:15:20.630 --> 01:15:23.150 align:middle line:84%
with this property
that is divergent.

01:15:23.150 --> 01:15:26.560 align:middle line:84%
Because obviously, if
all the a n were 0,

01:15:26.560 --> 01:15:28.620 align:middle line:90%
it would be convergent.

01:15:28.620 --> 01:15:31.620 align:middle line:84%
But it still could
be another series

01:15:31.620 --> 01:15:36.210 align:middle line:84%
with a n's that have that
property that was divergent.

01:15:36.210 --> 01:15:40.180 align:middle line:84%
But in this case, it is
going to be convergent.

01:15:40.180 --> 01:15:41.860 align:middle line:90%
And why is it convergent?

01:15:41.860 --> 01:15:45.900 align:middle line:84%
Because this series
here is convergent.

01:15:45.900 --> 01:15:47.160 align:middle line:90%
We have already seen that.

01:15:47.160 --> 01:15:50.250 align:middle line:84%
So this here would be like
the simple comparison test,

01:15:50.250 --> 01:15:52.810 align:middle line:90%
like the comparison test.

01:15:52.810 --> 01:15:58.830 align:middle line:90%


01:15:58.830 --> 01:16:04.050 align:middle line:84%
So these are just examples of
things you should be reviewing.

01:16:04.050 --> 01:16:09.555 align:middle line:84%
They are-- like these things
here, the two things to the end,

01:16:09.555 --> 01:16:11.400 align:middle line:90%
like this one here--

01:16:11.400 --> 01:16:14.580 align:middle line:84%
this is super fast, so
don't expect it to be

01:16:14.580 --> 01:16:16.970 align:middle line:90%
quite as fast on the midterm.

01:16:16.970 --> 01:16:22.310 align:middle line:84%
But it just gives you an idea
of what you should be doing.

01:16:22.310 --> 01:16:25.000 align:middle line:90%